<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relatives of Taiwan Woman Consent to Autopsy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Relatives of Lin Ti-chuan, a
Taiwan woman who was reportedly kidnapped and died in Haicheng, a
city in northeast China's Liaoning Province on July 29, today
consented to an autopsy which the Liaoning law enforcement
officials believe will help determine the exact causes of death
and provide critical material evidence.
</P>
<P>
Related departments in Haicheng, the city in which Lin was
abducted and died as the result of an alleged economic dispute,
have consulted with Lin's relatives since their arrival on August
1. Lin's relatives agreed to the autopsy after consulting with
local legal and medical experts.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached an agreement this afternoon, with
Huang Zhaoxing representing the slain woman's family. A press
conference was held a short time later to brief journalists.
</P>
<P>
The agreement says Haicheng departments investigating the
case will arrange the autopsy on Lin's body, with Chen Yaochang, a
friend on the family, observing related procedures.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls a timetable for completing the autopsy and
returning the remains to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Lin's relatives expressed gratitude for the support and
assistance granted by Haicheng officials over the past several
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
