<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Overseas Chinese Want Children to Learn Native Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Just as most German children,
Tian Tian, an 11-year-old overseas Chinese boy living in
Nuremberg, Germany, enjoys computers and basketball. But unlike
his foreign counterparts, she must learn Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Tian Tian finds it difficult to learn Chinese
characters. Nonetheless, the young boy has learned more than 1,000
characters, and can read Chinese newspapers. In addition, two
of his compositions have been published in the overseas edition of
Beijing-based People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
Tian Tian and his parents have been invited to visit Beijing to
participate in a summer language camp organized by People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
The young boy and 80 overseas Chinese children from the United
States, Japan, Canada, Britain and France will study the
language, culture, history and geography of China.
</P>
<P>
"Tian Tian arrived in Germany at the age of two and few
difference remain between him and his German friends," said Pang
Xiaobin, his mother. "We're Chinese and it is imperative
for him to learn Chinese."
</P>
<P>
"He has few opportunities to learn Chinese in Germany, so we
teach him at home. We also speak Chinese at home," said Pang.
</P>
<P>
She expressed hope that Tian Tian will learn another 3,000
Chinese characters and be able to easily communicate in the
language within the next three years. Reaching the goal will
require Tian Tian to learn three characters per day over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
Although not exactly fond of language study, Tian Tian loves
Chinese food and he often invites his German friends home for
dinner.
</P>
<P>
"We want to maintain more Chinese traditions, and have brought
Tian Tian to China every year since 1992. This time we want him
receive a patriotic education and hope the camp will develop his
interest in Chinese culture," said Pang.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of overseas Chinese children can
understand and speak Chinese, while a much lower percentage can
read and write, said Chen, who hopes to provide more opportunities
for children to study Chinese.
</P>
<P>
In addition to learning spoken Chinese and calligraphy, writing
compositions and exchanging overseas experienced, the children will
visit the Palace Museum, Summer Palace, Great Wall and Temple of
Heaven, in addition to viewing the national flag-raising ceremony
in Tian'anmen Square.  
</P>
</TEXT>
