<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Offers Composite Dialogue With Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee Monday offered a direct and composite dialogue
with Pakistan to resolve all outstanding issues, including Jammu
and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue must address the totality of the relationship and
not be pursued in a narrow, segmented fashion which would defeat
its very purpose of building a wide-ranging and enduring
relationship, Vajpayee told upper and lower houses of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
A direct bilateral interaction covering Indo-Pakistan
differences in a rational and realistic manner and seeking
confidence-building through cooperation in functional areas and
people-to-people contact would help create a positive climate for
purposefully addressing difficult issues under discussion between
the two sides, according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Replying to clarification sought by parliamentarians on his
statement on the 10th summit of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in Colombo, Sri Lanka, last week,
Vajpayee rejected any third party mediation to resolve the Kashmir
issue.
</P>
<P>
On recent conflicts in Kashmir between the two neighbors, the
Indian prime minister put the blame on Pakistan, saying the border
attacks by Pakistan would be firmly dealt with.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said his government would take all measures to
safeguard lives to people along the line of actual control, and
that security forces would be fully backed in their efforts to
repulse Pakistan's nefarious designs.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that diplomatic initiatives taken by his government
after India's nuclear tests in May had brought about a greater
understanding of New Delhi's position.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee informed the parliament that during his talks with
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on July 29 on the sidelines
of the 10th SAARC summit in Colombo, he reiterated India's
commitment to developing peaceful and friendly ties with Pakistan
and New Delhi's interest in a "secure, stable and prosperous
Pakistan".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
