<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Concerned with Tension in Cyprus: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A Russian envoy Monday expressed
concern over increasing tension on the Cyprus island, but defended
his country's sale of the surface-to-air missile system to Greek
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting here with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides, Russian Foreign Ministry envoy for
Cyprus Vladimir Tchizhov said Nicosia's decision to buy the S-300
missiles is not the reason for tension in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"The S-300s are not the reason for which the dialog stopped and
there is no movement for a Cyprus settlement," Tchizhov said.
</P>
<P>
He added the "tension will exist for as long as the impasse
continues and it is possible that it will increase."
</P>
<P>
The Russian envoy also expressed concern with the lack of
progress in the Cyprus peace effort and said "today we are a step
behind where we were a year ago."
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of talks between Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders
were held in the U.S. and Switzerland last year, but produced no
breakthrough. Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of
the talks to protest against a European Union (EU) decision to
start membership talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said he will not participate in peace talks
unless his breakaway state in northern Cyprus is recognized and
Cyprus withdraws its application to join the EU.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been mounting on the island since the missile
contract was struck early last year. The missiles are is scheduled
to be deployed on the east Mediterranean island late this year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which landed troops and seized the north third of the
island in 1974 in the wake of an abortive coup seeking union with
Greece, and has maintained some 35,000 troops there, threatened to
launch preemptive strike to prevent the missiles'' deployment.
</P>
<P>
Tchizhov reiterated Moscow's support to the efforts exerted by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to settle the Cyprus problem and
said Russia backs the island's demilitarization.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriots-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974. Turkey Cypriots
declared a breakaway state in 1983, which was recognized only by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
