<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Law Banning Strikes Said to Be Gazetted in Error </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Recently gazetted laws banning
strikes in essential services and giving police wide powers to
control public gatherings and demonstrations in Zimbabwe were
published in error, the attorney-general's office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Attorney-General Patrick Chinamasa said the
purported statutory instruments, namely the emergency powers in
declaration of essential service notice, law and order
maintenance for control of firearms and explosives and the law
and order maintenance on holding of public gatherings regulations
were invalid.
</P>
<P>
He said, "none of the instruments was seen or approved by the
responsible minister or the president, so apart from being
erroneous their publication was invalid and does not in any way
represent the policy of the government."
</P>
<P>
Authoritative sources Monday said they were surprised by the
publication of the regulations as they had never been debated in
cabinet, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"It was quite a bad mix-up which has caused a lot of damage to
the country's image," said a source in the Office of the
President and Cabinet, adding that President Robert Mugabe was
livid when he first saw the reports about the laws as he had
never seen or sanctioned them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rediscount Rate Increased in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's central bank Monday
increased its rediscount rate from 31.5 to 35 percent with
immediate effect as part of efforts to arrest further
depreciation of the Zimbabwean Dollar against major currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe said in statement that the Zimbabwean
Dollar had recently come under speculative pressure resulting in
further depreciation to levels "beyond those compatible with
economic fundamentals and developments in international currency
markets".
</P>
<P>
This situation had left the bank with no option but to increase
the rediscount rate in order to bring stability to the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
This also came on the back of a weaker South African Rand,
Zimbabwe's major trading currency partner and rising domestic
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Real rates had also been eroded due to a progressive increase in
domestic prices from 20.1 percent in December 1997 to about 30
percent in 1998, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
