<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Promises Continued Help for Angolan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Lakhdar Brahimi, the United
Nations special envoy, said here Monday that U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan would continue his effort in solving
the crisis of the Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
The visiting U.N. official said after delivering Annan's
letter to Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos that Annan is
concerned about the crisis in the peace process in the country.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi said Santos has promised that the Angolan government
would do its best to carry out the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi arrived in Luanda Saturday for a five-day visit to get
first-hand information about the current crisis in the country's
peace process.
</P>
<P>
He has met separately with Kofi Obeng, the temporary chairman
of the joint committee of Angolan peace process, representatives
of the three observation countries of the U.S., Russia and
Portugal.
</P>
<P>
He would also meet Jonas Savimbi, chairman of the National
Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) in central
Angola's Andulo city Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The current crisis in Angola has been triggered by UNITA's
refusal to hand over four "sensitive cities" to the government
and maintaining its military forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
