<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Unilaterally Declares Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government
unilaterally declared a ceasefire with rebels in southern Sudan on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The truce will start on Tuesday "to contain the humanitarian
situation in southern Sudan," where at least 1 million people are
facing starvation, said a government statement, but without
mentioning the duration of the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
In a press release Minister of State with the Sudanese Foreign
Ministry Ali Al-Nomeiri expressed his government's hope that the
Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA) would respond to the
government decision to make the ceasefire a permanent one in south
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The decision will serve to facilitate the opening of
check-points and passages for the human relief workers, Al-Nomeiri
said, describing the situation as very bad in the area.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came on the eve of the August 4-6 negotiations
between the warring parties in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia with an aim
to end the 15-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA led by John Garang is now the only rebel group
continuing fighting the government for autonomy of the
predominantly Christian and animist region from the Muslim
north. At least 1.5 million people have died since the insurgence
started in 1983.
</P>
<P>
There are about 2.6 million people in southern Sudan suffering
from lack of food. Fighting and drought are making the situation
worse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
