<HEADLINE> Israel, Romania Intend to Enhance Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Romanian leaders
held talks here Monday in a bid to enhance trade ties between the
their two countries.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu hosted a welcome
ceremony in his office for his visiting Romanian counterpart Radu
Vasile before their meeting.
</P>
<P>
Vasile was accompanied by a delegation of nine cabinet
ministers and other senior officials, which put the development of
bilateral trade with Israel at the top of its agenda.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Vasile will inaugurate a special
representative office in Israel, which will provide information on
hundreds of Romanian projects and government companies to be
privatized, in order to draw investment from Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel Aircraft Industries also plans to send three technical
teams to Romania next month to pursue efforts to sell Bucharest
its military and civilian aviation systems.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Israel and Romania totaled about 55 million
U.S. dollars during the first three months of 1998, and reached
260 million dollars throughout 1997.
</P>
<P>
Vasile, who began a four-day visit to Israel on Sunday, also
said that Romania is willing to return property to its Jewish
citizens, whose property was nationalized after World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
