<HEADLINE> Rwanda Denies Involving in Congo (K) Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
strongly rejected accusations by Democratic Congo that its troops
are behind the on-going rebellion in the capital Kinshasa and
eastern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis now rising in Kinshasa and the Eastern part of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) is purely an internal matter,
and the government of Rwanda is not involved in it any way," a
statement issued by Rwandan Minister of Foreign Affairs Anastase
Gasana Monday afternoon said.
</P>
<P>
The Rwanda News Agency, in a dispatch to Xinhua here, quoted
the statement as saying that Rwanda, as a good neighbor, provided
assistance to the Congolese to topple late Zairean dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko from power.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Rwanda is happy that the Congolese are now
liberated," said the statement, which was read by the radio in
French and Swahili.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government provides support to Congo (K) which is
still faced with hostile forces opposing its rebirth, the
statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The government of Rwanda claims that for a period of a year,
and basing on the fact that the Congolese now can handle their
own problems alone, it withdrew her military training force from
the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"The complete departure of the said Rwandan military force was
organized and supervised by Congolese senior officers, who
provided it with necessary logistics and transport facilities and
accompanied it, satisfactorily to both parties, back to Rwanda,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, troops opposing Kabila, have rebelled in Goma
and Bukavu towns, bordering Rwanda, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The border between Rwanda and DRC has been closed, and about
500 people are said to have crossed into Rwandan town of
Cyangugu, fearing that fighting might broke out in Bukavu.
</P>
</TEXT>
