<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls for End to Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordan on Monday called for an end
to the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister for Development Affairs and
Minister of Foreign Affairs Jawad Anani said the sanction problem
is the the most outstanding issue that must be solved now.
</P>
<P>
He called for the solving of all the problems left over by the
Gulf War (1990-91) in a statement released to the official Petra
news agency on the 8th anniversary of Iraq's occupation of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions have brought too much suffering to the Iraqi
people and should be lifted as soon as possible, said Anani.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when the U.N. chief weapons inspector
Richard Butler is meeting with Iraqi officials in Baghdad on the
destruction of weapons of mass destruction in the country.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions can only be lifted when the U.N. inspectors
verify that Iraq is free of those weapons.
</P>
<P>
Another big problem left over by the Gulf War is the detention
of Kuwaiti war prisoners in Iraq, which has made many Kuwaiti
families heart-broken year after year, Anani said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq should release the prisoners in a short time to make their
families reunite, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has said Iraq has been detaining over 600 Kuwaitis since
the end of the Gulf War, but Iraq has denied the claim.
</P>
<P>
Overcoming the problems involving Kuwait and Iraq, two Arab
countries, is very important for the future of the Arab world,
said Anani.
</P>
<P>
All the concerned sides should contribute efforts in this
regard in order to help establish an "Arab reconciliation," the
minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
