<HEADLINE> Lebanese Leaders Inquire Saudi King's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi,
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, on Monday inquired about the heath of
King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz, the Lebanese National News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The ailing king, 77, was admitted to hospital for medical
check-up on Sunday for the second time in less than six months,
and underwent a successful colon operation on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi and Hariri telephoned Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah,
Defense Minister Prince Sultan separately.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi leaders reportedly told the Lebanese leaders that the
king's condition was stable, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
King Fahd has been suffering from poor health for several
years. He underwent gall bladder surgery in 1994 and suffered a
stroke in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
In January 1996, he handed over the affairs of state to Crown
Prince Abdullah but re-assumed power seven weeks later.
</P>
<P>
His health has long been in the limelight in the world as his
rich country enjoys some one third of global oil reserve. 
</P>
