<HEADLINE> U.N. General Assembly President Visits Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The current President of the
United Nations General Assembly Guinadi Audvedenko Monday arrived
here on a visit at the invitation of Lebanese Foreign Minister
Fares Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
According to the state-run National News Agency, Boueiz will
request the senior U.N. official to exert maximum efforts in order
to master international support for Lebanon's stance over the
recent Israeli withdrawal proposal.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis offered to pull out of south Lebanon but linked
the implementation of U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 with
Lebanese government's security guarantee for their northern
borders.
</P>
<P>
This was rejected by Lebanon and its ally Syria, who insisted
that the withdrawal must be unconditional, as called for by the
resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The United States and U.N. chief Kofi Annan, however, have
called the Israeli offer a positive step.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria therefore launched an international campaign
to confront the Israeli "maneuver" and called on the
international community to press Israel to fully abide by the
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz believed the weighty U.N. General Assembly can have,
through Audvedenko's high position, a considerable leverage to let
the Jewish state pull its troops from Lebanon, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 after two invasions, with the claimed aim of
protecting its northern villages from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit, Audvedenko will hold meetings with
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi, House Speaker Nabih Berri and
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
