<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will construct a pipeline that will quadruple
the natural gas production in the North Sinai area.
</P>
<P>
The new pipeline will carry natural gas byproducts from the
offshore gas fields of Port Said on the Mediterranean, run below
the Suez Canal, and reach the eastern part of the canal and Sinai.
</P>
<P>
The new project is designed to transfer the new gas
explorations of Port Said to fields that will produce four times
as much gas, namely, from a current 112 million cubic feet per
day, to 463 million cubic feet per day, Minister of Petroleum
Hamdi Al Banbi said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Banbi, who paid a visit to the governorate of North Sinai,
added the gas pipeline is to carry gas byproducts as part of the
national gas network at a cost of 164 million dollars and will
take two years to complete.
</P>
<P>
The project will also provide for the needs of power stations
and industrial zones west and east of the Suez Canal and North and
South Sinai, he said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The General Authority for Investment and Free Zones
Chairman Ibrahim Fawzi has said non-Arab foreign contributions to
investment projects in Egypt increased to 651 million U.S. dollars
in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
This indicates an increase of 25 percent compared with the same
period of last year, Fawzi told a meeting Saturday night with
members of the American-Egyptian Chamber of Commerce in Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
The Authority is currently negotiating with the French auto
manufacturer Peugeot on setting up a car motor plant at Ismailia
free-trade zone in northeastern Egypt, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fawzi pointed out that doubling Egyptian exports to foreign
markets is a main target of the government.
</P>
<P>
He said the Egyptian government is studying a report by the
authority on the importance that companies specialized in
exporting to foreign markets should enjoy tax breaks, privileges,
guarantees and the incentives provided for in the Investment Law
No. 8 for 1997.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen's Ministry of Oil and Mineral Resources
predicted that the exportation of the Yemeni gas will start in
2003. This is the first time the government admits the delay of
the project which was originally slated for 2001.
</P>
<P>
Monday's Al-Hayat newspaper quoted a report of the ministry as
saying that 5.3 million tonnes of gas is expected to be exported
annually which will bring in revenue, according to the government
forecasts, between 650 and 750 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
