<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS -- Between 1987 and 1997 a total of 93 of Tunisia's
public enterprises were privatized wholly or partially with the
revenue from this process amounting to some 398 million dinars
(343 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics of the Tunisian Economic
Development Ministry, the annual rate of privatized firms rose
from six enterprises between 1987 to 1994 to 15 over the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Managing Director of National Iranian Steel Company
Mostafa Moazenzadeh announced Monday that the country has produced
1.5 million tonnes of steel products out of 1.8 million tonnes of
unprocessed steel in the first four months of the current Iranian
year (starting from March 21).
</P>
<P>
He said that about 5.5 million tonnes of steel products were
produced last year, expressing hope that export of steel products
would earn the country 350 million dollars in this Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's foreign exchange revenue will drop to 9
billion dollars this Iranian year from 14 billion dollars in the
previous year, deputy governor of the Central Bank of Iran
Mohammad Jafar Mojarad stated here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA quoted him as saying that 3.5
billion dollars out of the total sum would be allocated for import
of basic commodities this year.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that Iran would have a foreign revenue deficit of
3 to 3.5 billion dollars in the year, adding that to solve the
problem, various measures would be taken including use of the
foreign exchange assets and sale of oil in advance.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Sanctions Committee of the United Nations has just
approved another three contracts, under which some Jordanian
companies will provide Iraq with 488,000 U.S. dollars worth of
medicine and other commodities, an official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
These contracts were signed and ratified under the framework
of the oil-for-food deal, under which Iraq is allowed to sell 5
billion dollars worth of oil every six months to buy humanitarian
goods such as food and medicine, Jordan's official news agency
quoted the anonymous official from the Ministry of Industry and
Trade as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
