<HEADLINE> 62,653 Tanzanian Civil Servants Retrenched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has retrenched 62,653 civil servants from its bloated
bureaucracy, Minister of State for Central Establishment Mateo
Qaresi announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moving 1998/99 budget estimates for his office at the National
Assembly in central Dodoma, he said the civil servants were laid
off from the central and local governments between 1993 and this
year.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament, however, that the government will no
longer lay off civil servants on a large scale unless the number
of them is found to be in excess, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Qaresi said his office has established that some of those
retrenched are yet to be paid their rightful dues and appealed to
the affected to send relevant particulars for payment.
</P>
<P>
The minister promised that the government will take
disciplinary action against those who willingly postpone issuing
benefits to the retrenchees.
</P>
<P>
Next January, the government will introduce an open
performance appraisal system to increase working efficiency of
civil servants, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government is preparing a "result oriented
management" system which will specify job description of every
civil servant, Qaresi said.
</P>
<P>
The system to be applicable in all ministries and independent
departments is geared toward more efficiency and productivity.
</P>
<P>
Qaresi said his office has established a unit responsible for
overseeing observation of ethics in offices with a view to
enforcing standing regulations and procedures.
</P>
<P>
Since the unit was established in January this year, it has
received numerous complaints from the public and workers with
regard to corruption, indiscipline, absenteeism and drunkenness,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Permanent Commission of Inquiry received
3,727 complaints in the last fiscal year (from July of 1997 to
June of 1998), 927 of which have been dealt with and 2,810 are
being heard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
