<HEADLINE> Russia Calls for Dialogue Over Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Monday urged India and
Pakistan to settle their territorial disputes over Kashmir through
dialogue, but said the recent shootouts on the border were "no
reason for panic".
</P>
<P>
"The firing over the past few days is certainly a negative
development," Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said,
"but such incidents occur in the Summer, when snow melts in the
mountains and it becomes easier to cross the border."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated Moscow's call for dialogue over Kashmir, noting
that both sides seem to be ready to talk, the Interfax new agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Clashes have increased along the line of control since India
and Pakistan conducted nuclear tests in May, with each country
accusing the other of firing across the line first.
</P>
<P>
In the latest development, the Associated Press of Pakistan
(APP) said that the Pakistan army "blasted" an Indian base and
killed a large number of troops on Monday in an exchange of firing
in the Kashmir region.
</P>
<P>
APP said the Monday action was in response to "unprovoked
Indian firing" across a military control line, adding that at
least three people were killed on the Pakistan-controlled side of
Kashmir on Monday by Indian firing, raising the toll in five days
to 60.
</P>
<P>
India has put the death toll on their side at more than 30,
reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
