<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mogadishu Administration Set up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Candidates for the
administration of Somali capital Mogadishu were announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Mohamed Aidid and Ali Mahdi Mohamed were nominated as
the two co-chairmen of the supreme council, while Mohamed Qanyare
Afrah, Abdi Osman Farah, Osman Ali Atto and Musa Sudi Yalahow
were named as their deputies.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 people including faction leaders Osman Ali Atto
and Muss Sudi Yalahow from all parts of the country have been
included in the supreme council for Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Ali Ahmed was officially nominated as the governor of
the capital and Colonel Abdi Hassan Awale named to be the head
of the future police force of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The date for the opening of the main installations of
Mogadishu, the airport and sea ports, are supposed to be August 4
or tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
This is the most difficult issue since Osman Ali Atto and many
other rivals within all factions of Mogadishu are trying to
oppose this administration.
</P>
<P>
The political situation in the Somali capital has been sketchy
following an exhaustingly long meeting by the faction leaders
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, attended by faction leaders like Ali Mahdi
Mohamed, Hussein Mohamed Aidid, Osman Ali Atto, Mohamed Qanyareh
Afrah and many others, was aimed at concluding the formation of
Mogadishu's long-awaited administration.
</P>
<P>
Even though the meeting was behind closed doors, sources close
to the faction lenders said a serious argument over who would
sign the 10-page document for the transitional charter of the 16
districts of the capital has led to the abandonment of the
meeting by Osman Ali Atto.
</P>
<P>
The meeting then continued without Osman Ali Atto. And the
rest agreed to fill Osman Atto's seat with his interior secretary
Colonel Abdi Hassan Awale Qeybdid who fell out with his boss for
the modalities of Mogadishu's administration.
</P>
<P>
At 16:00 hours local time Monday, the faction leaders met
again at Villa Somalia, the former headquarters of the late
regime and the current base of Hussein Mohamed Aidid, where a
ceremony for the announcement of an administration for Mogadishu
was held.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Abdi Qeybdid, the interior secretary of Osman Ali
Atto, was the last to arrive to fill Osman Atto's place.
</P>
<P>
In the ceremony, Ahmed Dahir Kiar, the former secretary of
Hussein Aidid and the secretary of the new council, read the
names of the administration and its charter for the crowd.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of cheering people, hundreds of heavily armed
militiamen with more than one hundred battle wagons have gathered
around the headquarters of Hussein Mohamed Aidid for the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
Loud speakers mounted in the area played the national anthem,
patriotic songs and those especially sung for festivals. Dozens
of street vendors with wheel barrows and other mobile grapefruit
juice makers also made the scene exceptionally vivid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
