<HEADLINE> Burns: U.S., Greece Can Work Well in Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Greece could
work together well in the future, U.S. ambassador in Greece
Nicholas Burns said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his talks with Greek Foreign Undersecretary
Yiannos Kranidiotis, Burns described as "excellent" the talks
which covered a wide range of issues including Greek-U.S.
relations, Greek -Turkish relations and the Cyprus problem, the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Burns, who also had talks with Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos last week, said that U.S. and Greece were working very
closely on all these problems.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador added that his talks with both Pangalos and
Kranidiotis were evidence that the recent tension in Greek-U.S.
relations was over, and the two countries "can and will work
together well in the future."
</P>
<P>
Pangalos criticized recently U.S. President Bill Clinton for
not fulfilling his promise to solve the Cyprus problem, and
Washington reacted angrily that such remarks could damage the good
relations between the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
