<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Foreign Direct Investment 46 Pct Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Outward foreign direct
investment by European Union member countries in 1997, both inside
and outside the union, was 46 percent up as against 1996, Eurostat
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the European
communities said that the EU direct investment for last year
totalled 172.272 billion ECU (189.499 billion U.S. dollars),
outpacing inward foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
Inward foreign direct investment for 1997 totalled 99.164
billion ECU (109.08 billion dollars), or 38 percent up compared
with a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Britain dominated outward foreign direct investment with 31.546
billion ECU, followed by Germany and France with 29.276 billion
ECU and 28.139 billion ECU respectively.
</P>
<P>
Germany continued as the biggest net exporter of foreign direct
investment capital with 29.442 billion ECU (32.386 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Total outward investment flows rose in all EU member states
except for Belgium and Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Belgium and Luxembourg both posted a negative increase of
outward foreign direct investment of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Six EU member states, Belgium, Luxembourg, Denmark, Italy, the
Netherlands and Finland invested more within the union than
outside.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
