<HEADLINE> Kok Sworn in as Dutch PM for 2nd Purple Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Wim Kok was sworn in on Monday
for a second term as the prime minister of the tripartite Purple
Coalition cabinet of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Also sworn in were 14 other cabinet ministers and 14 state
secretaries, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet will hold its first meeting on Tuesday and will
present its government policy to the lower house of the Dutch
parliament on August 25 when the legislature resumes after the
Summer recess.
</P>
<P>
The Kok-led coalition was formed by the Labor Party, the
People's Party for Freedom and Democracy and the Democrats 66.
</P>
<P>
The three parties had formed the previous coalition for a term
of four years during which the Purple Coalition won the trust of
the Dutch public.
</P>
<P>
Purple is the color blended by the colors of the party banners
of the three parties.
</P>
<P>
In the general elections held in May this year, the Labor Party
won 45 seats; the People's Party for Freedom and Democracy got 38
seats, and the Democrats 66 had 14 seats.
</P>
<P>
The trio combined to account for 97 of the 150 seats in the
lower house of the Dutch parliament.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition, the Christian Democratic Appeal, took 29
seats.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
