<HEADLINE> Liberian Minister Accuses Guinea of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Liberian Defense Minister Daniel
Chea has accused neighboring Guinea of planning to destabilize
his country, warning that Liberia would resist "militarily" any
destabilization attempt, a report reaching here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The minister was quoted as saying that his government would
"militarily resist any attempt by Guinea to destabilize Liberia
and plunge this nation into turmoil."
</P>
<P>
He added that "the Liberian security network has confirmed
intelligence reports from Guinea that about 800 individuals are
being trained in Guinea to be dispatched to Liberia under the
cover of ECOMOG (West African Peace Monitoring Force) to
overthrow the one-year-old government of Liberia."
</P>
<P>
Chea said in an interview published Monday on Liberian
newspapers that "there will be no additional ECOMOG troops,
especially from Guinea. Anything to the contrary will be met with
force."
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, Liberian President Charles Taylor
said that there was nothing wrong with armed security men on the
streets of Monrovia, arguing that "the security situation of
Liberia coming out of war is still a dangerous one."
</P>
<P>
Students and representatives of youth of the West African
country made appeals over the weekend, saying that the presence
of armed men on the streets remind them of the war.
</P>
<P>
But, Taylor said that most of those carrying arms on the
streets were former fighters drawn from all dissolved factions
and given at least five months of special training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
