<HEADLINE> 50 Nigerian Drivers Injured for Defying Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Up to 50 commercial drivers who
defied a strike order were injured Friday in southwest Nigeria's
Ibadan City, the official News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the trouble started in the Oke-Ado area when
some union members defied the strike order issued by the National
Union of Road Transport Workers by putting their vehicles on the
roads as early as 5 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
They were attacked and overwhelmed by pro-strike union
members, who also destroyed about 30 buses in the fracas that
lasted about 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The strike started Thursday in protest of fuel hoarding by
marketeers, the report said, adding that the angry strikers also
sealed off some filling stations.
</P>
<P>
Security agents have been deployed in parts of the city to
guard strategic areas and to maintain law and order, NAN said.
</P>
