<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, August 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei Monday
approved a government plan aimed at reviving the ailing
oil-dependent economy.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a letter of President Mohammad Khatami, Khamenei
termed all the points raised in the letter as sound and said that
he agreed to all of them, the official news agency IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei wished success for Khatami and his administration in
managing the economy and removing the obstacles in the way of its
development. (Iran-Leader-Economic Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The Sudanese government unilaterally declared a
ceasefire with rebels in southern Sudan on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The truce will start on Tuesday "to contain the humanitarian
situation in southern Sudan," where at least 1 million people are
facing starvation, said a government statement, but without
mentioning the duration of the ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
In a press release Minister of State with the Sudanese Foreign
Ministry Ali Al-Nomeiri expressed his government's hope that the
Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA) would respond to the
government decision to make the ceasefire a permanent one in south
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The decision will serve to facilitate the opening of
check-points and passages for the human relief workers, Al-Nomeiri
said, describing the situation as very bad in the area.
(Sudan-Ceasefire 1st lead writethru EDS: Add details, quotes of
official)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- President of the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) is to present the new cabinet to the Palestinian
Legislative Council (PLC) for approval on Wednesday, PLC Press
Office said in Ramallah on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During Wednesday's PLC special session in Ramallah, Arafat will
present to the Council the new cabinet, and possibly a ministerial
statement, and after discussions the PLC will vote on the new
cabinet, the Office said.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen of Arafat's 18 cabinet ministers offered their
resignations a year ago under pressure from legislators, but
Arafat took no action at the time. (Palestine-Arafat-New Cabinet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
