<HEADLINE> HSBC Holdings Reports Interim Pre-tax Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 3 (Xinhua) - HSBC Holdings plc made a profit
before tax of 3686 million US dollars in the first six months of
1998, a fall of 599 million, or 14 percent, over the same period
in 1997, Keith Whitson, Group Chief Executive said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, Whitson told reporters at a press conference that net
interest income of 5651 million US dollars was 406 million, or 8
percent, higher than the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Other operating income rose by 735 million US dollars, or 21
percent, to 4318 million US dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
The charge for bad and doubtful debts was 1146 million US
dollars, which was 889 million US dollars higher than in the first
half of 1997, reflecting the continuing downturn within Asia and
deterioration in asset quality in several economies, according to
an interim report released at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
Whitson also said the economic difficulties in Asia have had a
marked effect on the performance of certain parts of HSBC
Holdings' loan portfolio, but it "remains well placed within the
financial markets in which it operates."
</P>
<P>
While it is difficult to predict when Asia's economies will
recover, Whitson believes that "they will emerge after a period of
painful restructuring stronger and more competitive than before."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
