<HEADLINE> Angolan Govt Prefers Dialog in Peace Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Higino Carneiro, the deputy director of the government's
delegation to the joint committee of Angolan peace process, said
it is for this that the government has not retaliated against the
armed activities by the National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with the visiting U.N. special envoy Lakhdar
Brahimi, Carneiro said the government is waiting for a change
of UNITA's attitude, while keeping vigil to make sure things
do not go out of control.
</P>
<P>
He charged that about 600 people have died during the recent
military actions by UNITA men and 90 cities and towns formerly
handed over to the government have been re-captured by UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Carneiro said the massacre in which 215 people were
killed on July 21 in Bula of northern Angola's Lunda-Norte
Province was believed to be done by UNITA. But UNITA denied
having anything to do with the killings. 
</P>
