<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Bankers Strike over Loan Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Some 12,000 Kenyan unionizable
bank workers staged a strike Monday in a bid to force the
government to scrap a tax on their low-interest staff loans and
fringe benefits.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of customers waited outside their branch offices,
while senior management staff in commercial banks provided
essential foreign exchange services and dealt with client
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Joseph Ngutu held tripartite talks with leaders
of the bankers' umbrella union, the Central Organization of Trade
Unions (COTU) and the Federation of Kenya Employers (FKE), but
failed to find a solution to the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The executive committee of All Banks Shop Stewards, which
called the strike, rejected the tripartite arrangement.
</P>
<P>
At a separate meeting, committee chairman Jacob Opiyo pledged
"an all-out standoff until the matter is conclusively resolved."
</P>
<P>
The strike has affected 63 banks and non-bank financial
institutions, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign currency trade was severely hampered by the strike,
dealers said Monday. The central bank posted the Shilling at a
mean rate of 59.1500 against the U.S. Dollar from 59.0472 Friday.
</P>
<P>
A strike over the same issue paralyzed banking services
earlier this year but was called off when the government
suspended implementation of the tax.
</P>
<P>
The tax was re-imposed in June and a tax on other fringe
benefits was also introduced with the government citing the
current economic difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
