<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Condemns Killings in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government Monday condemned the latest "senseless" killings of
civilians in Rwanda, the Foreign Affairs Department said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government condemns these latest senseless
attacks on innocent civilians as blatant acts of terrorism,
calculated to destabilize the efforts of the Rwandan government
and people to achieve justice and reconciliation after the
genocide of 1994," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
According to latest reports, rebels in Rwanda said to be
linked to the former Rwandan government killed 102 people in an
attack on a rural village about 60 kilometers north of the
capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria urged all parties involved in the violence to cease
their actions immediately and to stop pursuing a course which
would further delay the establishment of lasting peace in the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
"It is the (South African) government's conviction that these
actions have a clearly detrimental effect on the efforts of the
continent as a whole to bring about a better life for all its
people," said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
