<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Amends Code to Spur Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian investment
authority said Monday that the amended investment proclamation
and incentive regulation will enhance domestic and foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to mark the kicking-off of the proclamation and
the regulation here, General Manager of the authority Tadesse
Haile said under the revised proclamation, areas such as
telecommunications, hydroelectric power generation and defense
industries which were off-limit to private investment are now
open to both foreign and domestic investors.
</P>
<P>
He said investors could engage in the telecommunication and
defense industry jointly with the Ethiopian government and that
those foreign nationals who are Ethiopian by birth would be
considered domestic investors.
</P>
<P>
The new proclamation and decree stipulate that additional
incentives will be given to entrepreneurs engaging in areas that
require big investment and have strategic significance, Haile
said.
</P>
<P>
He said entrepreneurs who invest in the new fields can import
capital goods and equipment free of custom's tax and the sectors
will also be free from income tax.
</P>
<P>
The general manager also said special attention is given to
invest in areas of education and health.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time that the investment code is revised by
the Ethiopian government.
</P>
<P>
The investment code which was published in 1992 was firstly
revised in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
