<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The foreign currency reserves of Israel rose by 57
million U.S. dollars in July, after falling by 215 million dollars
in June.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Haaretz quoted a report of Bank of Israel as
saying that at the end of July, the reserves totaled 21.379
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Despite a growth in unemployment, Israel's textile
industry is still in need of some 650 new workers.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey conducted by Israeli Manufacturers'
Association on Monday, shortages in a host of different
professions were reported by some 70 companies in all areas of the
country.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's diamond exports totaled 443 million
U.S. dollars in July, down 12 percent compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Local daily The Jerusalem Post quoted a report of Israeli
Industry and Trade Ministry as saying that from the beginning of
the year, diamond exports have slowed down due to a sharp drop in
exports to Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The European Union will finance a project to recycle
solid waste in Egypt at a total cost of 1.6 million Egyptian
pounds (some 470,000 dollars), Egypt's Middle East News Agency
quoted sources of the EU commission here as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed at creating new mechanisms for the
Egyptian Authority for Environmental Affairs to be used in dealing
with industrial effluents, added the sources.
</P>
<P>
The EU will contribute 4.7 million ECU (5.16 million dollars)
to 16 environment-conservation projects within its program for
l998.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen of the projects are to be implemented in the
Mediterranean countries and the two others in the Baltic region.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri decided
Monday to apply the 1997 tax exemptions law on projects in the
Southern Valley, to turn the country's vastly-desert southern
region into a tax haven.
</P>
<P>
According to the Law on Investment Guarantees and Incentives,
enterprises in the Southern Valley will be exempted from
commercial and industrial taxes for up to 20 years starting from
the beginning of their operation.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the General Authority for Investment Ibrahim Fawzi
told reporters Monday that a map has been drafted to designate the
areas which will enjoy these exemptions.
</P>
<P>
He added that this initiative was part of the government's
ongoing efforts to promote the development of strategic projects
at the Southern Valley.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The total investments in the field of electric power
in the Arab world is expected to hit 50 billion dollars by the
year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's "Al Alam Al Youm" daily quoted Mervat Badawi,
director of the Technical Department at the Arab Fund for Social
and Economic Development, as saying that the existing capacity of
electric power in the Arab world is 84,000 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
The figure is expected to mount to 167,000 megawatts in 2010
and to 195,000 megawatts in 2015, she added.
</P>
<P>
Arab governments and institutions, such as the Arab Fund for
Social and Economic Development, the World Bank and other
commercial banks, will fund such investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
