<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARATS Forwards Letter to SEF (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Strait (ARATS) today sent a letter to the
Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) in Taiwan, expressing "strong
dissatisfaction and regret" over the latter's performance related
to the recent death of Lin Ti-chuan.
</P>
<P>
Lin, a Taiwan woman, was allegedly kidnapped and consequently
died in Haicheng, northeast China's Liaoning Province, in late
July.
</P>
<P>
ARATS noted that it had received five letters from SEF between
July 30 and August 3 concerning Lin's tragic death.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary investigation indicates the Lin's death was the
direct result of a business dispute between Wei Diangang, Lin's
boyfriend, and Li Guangzhi, director of the Dalian representative
office of Haicheng's Huamei Industrial Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"Local public security departments are handling the unfortunate
incident as a criminal case and are extending every possible
effort to uncover clues and apprehend the perpetrator(s),"
according to the letter. It goes on to say that ARATS has sent deputy
secretary-general Liu Gangqi to Haicheng to ensure Lin's family
receives all possible assistance.
</P>
<P>
The letter notes that ARATS and relevant departments joined in
a coordinated efforts to ensure Lin's family and relatives enjoyed
convenient transit through Hong Kong and entry to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
"The allegations of some people in Taiwan that the family
encountered difficulties are absolutely untrue," according to the
letter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ARATS Forwards Letter to SEF (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It also points out that SEF letters have repeatedly contained
groundless accusations that ARATS has refused to allow its
staffers to assist Lin's family with the case.
</P>
<P>
"We hold that the usual practice is for ARATS and SEF to
entrust each other with the responsibility to protect the
respective rights, interests, safety and personal property of
Taiwan compatriots and mainland residents involved in
cross-Straits incidents," according to the letter.
</P>
<P>
It adds that "facts prove the practice to be an unimpeded and
effective method which is in line with the current situation for
the cross-Straits relations."
</P>
<P>
The letter stresses that ARATS has never sent staffers to Taiwan
to assist in cases involving the personal safety or property of
mainland residents, while SEF staffers have never visited the
mainland to assist in cases involving Taiwan compatriots.
</P>
<P>
"Despite your clear understanding on this point, you have
repeatedly sent letters containing false accusations," says the
letter. "People on both sides of the Straits feel deep remorse
over Lin's case and we hold that you are taking advantage of the
incident to deliberately create and exacerbate differences in
order to sow dissension between compatriots across the straits."
</P>
<P>
"We hereby express our strong dissatisfaction and regret," says
the letter.
</P>
<P>
It goes on to say that SEF has also accused public security
departments on the mainland of "attempting to force Lin's family
to agree to an autopsy."
</P>
<P>
"Autopsies are part of legal procedures public security
departments must follow when investigating murder cases," said the
letter. "Public security departments on the mainland went to great
links to obtain the consent of Lin's family."
</P>
<P>
It adds that "SEF should understand the situation and cease and
desist in attempts to disrupt the investigation."
</P>
<P>
ARATS pledged to continue efforts to return Lin's remains to
Taiwan in accordance the wishes of her family and relevant
mainland regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
