<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Navigation Suspended Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Surging flood water along the
Yangtze, China's longest river, today forced the suspension of
navigation in the Three Gorges dam area.
</P>
<P>
Both the temporary lock and water diversion canal at the Three
Gorges Dam were closed early this morning as a result of the
record flood peak of 4.58 cu.m per second.
</P>
<P>
Hydrological and meteorological forecasts indicate that the
current water flow rate will increase in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
From last night, more than 100 buses have been used to disperse
passengers stranded in the area.
</P>
<P>
Owning to the same reason, the area had experienced three
navigation suspensions totaled 21 days in July. However, various
forms of transportation had been used to disperse the over 200,000
stranded passengers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Chief Justice Rules White House Lawyers Must </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chief Justice William
Rehnquist of the U.S. Supreme Court ruled on Tuesday that White
House lawyers must testify in the probe of alleged presidential
sex and cover-up, even as an appeal continues.
</P>
<P>
In a verbal ruling, Rehnquist rejected an attempt to prevent or
at least delay the testimony of Bruce Lindsey, a longtime adviser
for President Bill Clinton, and Lanny Breuer, a White House damage
control expert.
</P>
<P>
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr had subpoenaed Breuer to
appear on Tuesday before the grand jury investigating accusations
that Clinton had an affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky and then pressured her and others to lie about it --
allegations Clinton has denied.
</P>
<P>
Both Breuer and Lindsey have testified previously to the grand
jury, but claimed the attorney-client privilege against divulging
confidential conversations with clients in refusing to testify
about some matters involving Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Starr's team has argued that as government lawyers, they should
be compelled to testify completely, and a federal judge and an
appeals court panel agreed. The White House has appealed that
decision to the Supreme Court and also asked for a stay that would
prevent the lawyers' testimony while the case proceeds.
Rehnquist's ruling denied that request.
</P>
<P>
However, Lindsey is not expected to be able to testify this
week as he is recovering from back surgery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Grants 45m ECU Humanitarian Aid to Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission approved
on Tuesday a humanitarian aid worth 45 million ECU (49.5 million
U.S. dollars) for Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The aid, to be managed by the European Community Humanitarian
Office, will be used to assist the people facing food shortages in
southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union, has granted 66 million ECU (72.6 million dollars)
of aid to Sudan so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The new aid will co-fund the activities of the World Food
Program and other international organizations working to alleviate
the hunger-stricken region of Bahr El Ghazal.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 20 million ECU (22 million dollars) will fund the
aid programs to be conducted by the World Food Program, the United
Nations Children's Fund and the International Committee of the Red
Cross, while 25 million ECU (27.5 million dollars) will fund a
special program concerning food aid and food security by the World
Food Program.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program estimated that 700,000 people needed
emergency food aid in rebel-controlled areas of Bahr El Ghazal as
of early June, as compared to 250,000 people at the start of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The organization plans to get 15,000 tons of food a month to
aid a target population of 2.4 million people in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said that a combination of drought and
escalating conflict has aggravated the food crisis in the Bahr El
Ghazal province in southern Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Red Cross Receives Flood Relief Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Red Cross Society of China
has received 50 million yuan in donations from the international
community for the nation's massive flood relief effort.
</P>
<P>
The donations include 250,000 Swiss Francs (167,000 US dollars)
from the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies, 37,000 tons of medical supplies from the Egyptian
government, 200,000 German Marks (112,000 US dollars) from the
German Red Cross Society, and one million US dollars in cash and
goods valued at 4.5 million U.S. dollars from three U.S.-based
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross Society of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region has also raised 600,000 yuan for flood victims, and
the Taiwan Red Cross Society is currently preparing to send
medical supplies and disaster relief materials.
</P>
<P>
Most of the donations have already been distributed to flood
ravaged areas.
</P>
<P>
The International Federation of the Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies have raised more than one million Swiss Francs for
China's flood-stricken areas since July 21.  
</P>
</TEXT>
