<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Industrial Index Slips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's industrial index, the
barometer of the country's economic performance, continued its
downward trend Tuesday, losing 216.97 points to close at 6655.60.
</P>
<P>
The stock market, Africa's second largest one, was quietly
active and again weaker Tuesday, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the industrial index was likely to continue on
its downward trend in the absence of news to excite the market.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe raised its rediscount rate Monday
by 3.5 percent points to 35 percent to defend the Zimbabwean
Dollar which had fallen by 12.5 percent under heavy speculative
attack.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Dollar fell to a nine-month low against the
U.S. Dollar on Monday due to heavy import demand and lack of
support from the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said commercial banks were likely to hike interest
rates to above 40 percent in the wake of an increase in the
rediscount rate, which is the rate at which they borrow from the
Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
Inflation has progressively increased over the last six months
from 20.1 percent in December last year to a five-year high of
29.8 percent in June, this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Worried by UNSCOM Report on Failure of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- France Tuesday expressed concern
over the statement by William Butler, chief of U.N. Special
Commission on disarmament in Iraq (UNSCOM), that the talks between
UNSCOM and Iraq almost collapsed.
</P>
<P>
``We are expecting fuller information from his (Butler's) side
when he presents his report to the U.N. Security Council Thursday
August 6 in New York,'' said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman
Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
She reminded both UNSCOM and Iraq that a good cooperation
between them is necessary and inevitable for the lifting of the
sanctions imposed by the U.N. Security Council on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Butler and his UNSCOM delegation cut short their stay in
Baghdad Tuesday after their talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz on the progress in the U.N. inspection mission broke
down Monday night.
</P>
<P>
He said that Aziz demanded him to tell the U.N. Security Council
to give Iraq a clean bill of health on its weapons programs, but he
rejected the request, citing that he had no such evidence.
</P>
<P>
Butler also said a proposal presented by him for accelerating
the process of disarmament had been rejected by Aziz. 
</P>
