<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Urges Cross-Straits Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Tang Shubei, executive
vice-president of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Strait (Arats), today urged parties on either sides of the Taiwan
Straits to hold talks on procedural issues concerning political
negotiations at the earliest possible date, to be followed by
talks on practical and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the seventh seminar on cross-Straits relations
which opened today in Beijing, Tang pointed out differences
between the two sides in political issues.
</P>
<P>
Arats President Wang Daohan and Koo Chen-fu, president of the
Straits Exchange Foundation (Sef) in Taiwan, have held a number
of talks on practical matters since 1993, but have failed to reach
agreements due to political differences, according to Tang.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the two sides will boldly address
political differences and hold talks on procedural issues
concerning political negotiations. This is the only way to truly
solve practical matter and gradually settle political differences,
said Tang.
</P>
<P>
He said cross-Straits relations have witnessed considerable
progress over the past decade, and noted the substantial increase
in personnel, economic and trade exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Tang said the existence of some differences and even conflicts
between the two sides because of ideological discrepancies
resulted from the extended separation, but stressed that progress
in cross-Strait relations fully complies with the desires of
people on both sides.
</P>
<P>
He said the 21st century will offer both opportunities and
challenges for the Chinese nation, and called for people on both
sides of the straits to join in a concerted effort to achieve
common prosperity and reunification of the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
