<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection Key to China's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese legislator has
called on governments at all levels to incorporate environmental
protection into their economic development plans.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice chairman of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), also called for firm action against
behavior which damages the environment. The high-ranking leader
made the comments at today's forum on implementation of the
environmental protection instructions President Jiang Zemin issued
on August 5, 1997.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that departments and governments at all levels
have accelerated efforts to expand afforested areas over the past
year in order to prevent further soil erosion and desertification,
with related efforts leading to significant improvements in the
ecological balance across the country.
</P>
<P>
"However, China still faces a grim task regarding efforts to
improve the natural environment, with overall environmental
conditions worsening despite efforts to tackle local problems,"
according to Buhe.
</P>
<P>
Deserts in northwest China, the Loess Plateau and areas in the
upper reaches of the Yangtze River are faced with the most serious
environmental problems in China.
</P>
<P>
Today's forum was jointly sponsored by the Publicity Department
of the Communist Party of China Central Committee, the National
People's Congress, the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference and several central government
departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
