<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Canadians Gloomy About Financial Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The majority of Canadians feel
that their financial situation has worsened, shows a poll released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They also think that they are worse off than their parents, and the
younger generation will be worse off than them, says the Angus Reid
poll for the Globe and Mail and CTV television network.
</P>
<P>
Canadians have a more gloomy view of personal financial
situation than they did in 1989, before the start of the recession
that upset the career plans and income hopes of hundreds of
thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
Despite claims by politicians that things have improved, the
pessimism about personal finances is pervasive, says the poll
conducted between July 15 and July 22 involving 1,515 adult
Canadians.
</P>
<P>
The poll shows that 54 percent respondents felt it
harder to make ends meet, up from 38 percent in 1989, while 15
percent felt the opposite, down from 24 percent. Thirty-one
percent said it was about the same, down from 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
A comparison study of the financial situation among generations
has also revealed a dramatic shift since 1989. Forty-four percent
said they were better off than their parents' generation, down
from 74 percent nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, 40 percent said their generation was worse off, up
from 13 percent, while 15 percent felt about the same, up from 12
percent.
</P>
<P>
Expectations for the younger generation have also darkened,
with 57 percent of the respondents saying they would be worse off,
as compared with 41 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen percent Canadians predicted that the next generation
would be better off, down from 28 percent. Twenty-three percent said
they thought it would be about the same. 
</P>
</TEXT>
