<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Quake Causes No Severe Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The magnitude 6.0 earthquake which
occurred in Jiashi County in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region Sunday has only caused relatively small property
losses, but no casualties, confirmed the local government.
</P>
<P>
Relief work is well under way in the seven townships affected
by the quake. By 00:30 this morning, the local seismological
bureau recorded 150 aftershocks, including two measuring 5.0 and
5.2 on the Richter scale respectively.
</P>
<P>
Three people were slightly injured, 229 sheep died, 360 houses
collapsed, and 39 small bridges, eight schools and two hospitals
were damaged in the quake, according to preliminary statistics.
</P>
<P>
The same area had been hit by successive quakes last year, said
local seismologists.
</P>
<P>
From January to April 1997, seven consecutive quakes with a
magnitude over six struck Jiashi County, causing scores of deaths
and the collapse of tens of thousands of houses, a rare
seismological phenomenon worldwide.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that most of the houses built after the quake
frenzy last year remain undamaged in the lastest quake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
