<HEADLINE> Regional Leaders Plan Summit on Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Southern African leaders are
planning a summit on the festering problems in the Great Lakes
region to be held Saturday in Zimbabwe's western resort of
Victoria Falls.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean government sources confirmed Tuesday that
preparations were underway for a summit on the Great Lakes region
to be hosted by President Robert Mugabe and that about seven
leaders including those from the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC), Rwanda and Uganda are expected.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of Tanzania, Zambia and Namibia were also invited, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, we can confirm that a summit on the Great Lakes region
has been planned for Saturday. The leaders are expected to start
arriving on Friday," said a Zimbabwean Foreign Ministry official
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The Great Lakes region, riven by ethnic hatred, is on the boil
again with DRC President Laurent Kabila facing a revolt from
ethnic Tutsi Banyamulenge troops in the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who came to power in May 1997 after a seven-month
guerilla campaign from the east of the former Zaire backed by
Rwanda and Uganda, has accused his former allies of fomenting
unrest among his troops, particularly the mutinous Tutsi ethnic
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean government sources said the Victoria Falls summit
was suggested by three unnamed regional leaders during the recent
southern Africa international dialog (smart partnership) meeting
in Swakopmund, Namibia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
