<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Babies Born Out of Wedlock in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Almost one out of every four
babies are born outside marriage now in the European Union,
Eurostat reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The demographic report, prepared together with the Council of
Europe, said that the rate of babies born out of wedlock was less
than 10 percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat, the Luxembourg-based statistical bureau of the
European communities, said that outside-marriage births are
increasing throughout the 15-nation union and the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The bureau described the trend as reflecting the growing
popularity of cohabitation.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat figure showed that one in two live births in
Sweden and Denmark is outside marriage while one in two births in
Norway and two out of three births in Iceland, both European
Economic Area countries, are out of the wedlock.
</P>
<P>
Europe-wide, the statistical bureau added, marriage is in
decline.
</P>
<P>
The crude marriage rate in 1980 was 6.3 per 1,000 people
whereas it was down by last year to 5.0 per 1,000 people. Only
Denmark registered an increase from 5.2 per 1,000 people in 1980
to 6.5 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sweden posted the lowest marriage rate of 3.6 per 1,000 people
among the European countries surveyed by the Eurostat and the
Council of Europe.
</P>
<P>
One of the most significant demographic changes, said Eurostat,
has been the fall in infant mortality, or deaths of babies under
the age of one. The mortality rate has halved or more in many
European countries in the last two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
