<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Situation in Kinshasa Returning to Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KINSHASA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The situation in Kinshasa,
capital of the Democratic Republic of Congo (D.R. Congo), is
gradually returning to normal two days after a mutiny allegedly
staged by the Tutsi Banyamulenge soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen people, including 11 Banyamulenges and three
government soldiers, were killed and several others wounded in the
fighting over the past two days, press here reported.
</P>
<P>
Some military barricades were lifted Tuesday morning and
traffic was increasing as the situation was calming down.
</P>
<P>
Security forces were continuing their sweeping operations
against the rebels in the capital Tuesday morning, particularly
in the Kinsuka district where the mutinous soldiers were
reportedly holding out.
</P>
<P>
A source from the United Nations humanitarian agency here said
that security forces took away four U.N. employees because they
were Banyamulenges.
</P>
<P>
Some government forces, apparently backed by Banyamulenge and
Rwandan soldiers, declared an open rebellion against the
government of President Laurent Kabila in the eastern regions of
Nord Kivu and Sud Kivu at the Rwandan border.
</P>
<P>
The rebellion came after Kabila ordered the military officers
of Rwanda, who helped him come into power 15 months ago, to leave
the country.
</P>
<P>
In a clear warning against Rwanda and Uganda, a government
spokesman Pierre-Victor Mpoyo Monday asked D.R. Congo's neighbors
"not to mistake the fight."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the spokesman accused Rwanda of being behind the
rebellion, which was denied by Kigali.
</P>
<P>
He said that the fight engaged by the D.R. Congo government was
for "the peace process of the Great Lake region", including
Rwanda, Burundi and the eastern part of D.R. Congo.
</P>
<P>
Both the rebels and the government Tuesday claimed control of
the capital of Sud-Kivu, Bukavu, which is situated on the border
with Rwanda, Burundi and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese Minister of Justice Mwenze Kongolo said that the
troops loyal to President Kabila had seized Bukavu back from the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
"The rebels are on the way of disappearing from Bukavu after
the intervention of the government troops," he said, adding that
the airport of Bukavu had "never fallen."
</P>
<P>
But he said that he did not have any information from Goma, the
capital of Nord-Kivu, where the headquarters of a rebellious
battalion was located.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have vowed to put an end to Kabila's rule in the
two provinces and said they would also take the neighboring
province of Maniema.
</P>
<P>
During an extra-ordinary session of his cabinet Monday, Kabila
said he intended to end the rebellion in the east by force,
official sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
