<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lin Ti-chuan Autopsy Scheduled for Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- An autopsy on the body of Lin
Ti-chuan, a Taiwan woman allegedly kidnapped and consequently died
in Haicheng, northeast China's Liaoning Province, on July 29, is
scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's press conference, Liu Linlin, deputy
director of the Anshan Municipal Public Security Bureau in
Liaoning, said a panel of five prestigious legal and medical
experts has been formed to conduct the autopsy.
</P>
<P>
The panel members from a noted medical university, the Ministry
of Public Security and local police units, are all noted
pathologists or experts on medical jurisprudence.
</P>
<P>
A number of the members have been engaged in medical
jurisprudence for several decades, with others noted for their
expertise in advanced criminal investigation technologies,
including DNA testing, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the panel has drafted out an autopsy plan
in strict accordance with relevant laws, and that Chen Yaochang, a
friend of the family and noted medical law expert from Taiwan
University, will observe the proceeding on behalf of Lin's family.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Boku, director of the Anshan Taiwan Affairs Office, has
also been invited to witness to the autopsy, according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
The wishes of Lin's family will be honored and the autopsy will
be conducted at the Haicheng City Central Hospital, rather than
the Anshan Judicial Examination and Appraisal Center which offers
better facilities.
</P>
<P>
China's Criminal Law and Criminal Procedural Law defines
autopsies as a necessary procedure which enable law enforcement
departments investigating criminal cases to obtain sufficient
evidence and lead to the prosecution of criminal offenders in
accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
Lin's relatives arrived in Haicheng on August 1 and reached an
agreement with related city departments on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Liu expressed deep condolences, and thanked family members for
their cooperation with the local public security departments.
</P>
<P>
Lin's remains will be transported to Beijing following
tomorrow's autopsy and returned to Taiwan on August 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
