<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cross-Straits Relations Reviewed (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Relations between both sides of
the Taiwan Straits continued to develop in an all-round way in the
first half of this year because of advocacy by the Chinese
mainland of bilateral political negotiation and direct exchanges
of postal service, trade, air and shipping services, reports the
current issue of "Outlook."
</P>
<P>
This year, The Chinese mainland convened the first session of
the Ninth National People's Congress and the first session of the
Ninth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, formed a cross-century central leadership
and maintained a stable currency.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton held fruitful talks with Chinese
President Jiang Zemin during his nine-day state visit to China,
the article states, and Clinton reiterated the "one-China" policy
and the commitment of abiding by the three Sino-US joint
communiques.
</P>
<P>
All these provide a favorable environment for the development
of cross-straits relations, the article states, and shows a sign
of hope for bilateral political negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland has adopted a series of measures to speed
up the process of officially ending the hostile state between both
sides of the Taiwan Straits under the principle of "one China"
since the latter half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The move has evoked great repercussions in Taiwan, the article
says. Public polls show that more than half of Taiwan residents
favor political negotiation between the two sides and 70 percent
of those interviewed agreed to direct exchanges of postal, trade,
air travel and shipping services. People of all social sectors in
Taiwan consider that businesslike talks are no longer suitable to
the development between both sides of the Taiwan Straits, the
article says.
</P>
<P>
More contacts between the Association for Relations Across the
Taiwan Straits (ARATS) and Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) have
been conducted recently.
</P>
<P>
ARATS President Tang Shubei said that both sides are working
toward a common ground for political negotiation. Some leading
officials in Taiwan said on many occasions that political talks
are unavoidable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cross-Straits Relations Reviewed (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Non-governmental cultural, economic and trade exchanges between
both sides of the Taiwan Straits have increased since the
beginning of this year. More Taiwan compatriots, including members
of the Kuomintang and the Democratic Progressive Party, have
visited the Chinese mainland in the capacity of scholars, the
article states.
</P>
<P>
A large delegation composed of academics and professors of
universities in Taiwan attended the centennial anniversary of
Beijing University held in Beijing last May.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland remains the major source of Taiwan's
favorable trade balance. The indirect trade volume between the two
sides in 1997 totaled 24.5 billion U.S. dollars, with more than 20
billion dollars of Taiwan exports.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade volume registered substantial growth in the
first four months of this year. The Chinese mainland's exports to
Taiwan rose 26.4 percent, while imports from the latter were up 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of Taiwan-invested projects opened on the Chinese
mainland so far this year doubled that of last year and the amount
of funds involved increased by 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
The article quotes Taiwan statistics that show in the first
four months of this year Taiwan approved the establishment of 211
projects in various parts of China's mainland, involving a total
investment of 467 million U.S. dollars, 108 million dollars more
than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, people of all walks of life on the Chinese mainland
have enhanced cooperation with their counterparts in Taiwan by
visiting the island, the article states. A delegation of mass
media visited Taiwan last April, and more than 100 accomplished
scientists from the Chinese Academy of Sciences attended a seminar
on scientific and technological achievements held in Taipei in
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland will continue to implement the principle
of "placing hope on Taiwan people," accelerate bilateral
non-governmental exchanges, help Taiwan compatriots have a better
understanding of the Chinese mainland and the "one country, two
systems" formula and promote peaceful reunification of the
motherland, the article states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
