<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Rejects Israel's Latest Proposal on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) has rejected the latest proposal by Israel on the second
troop redeployment in the West Bank, Israel Radio reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Hassn Asfour, Palestinian coordinator of
peace negotiations, as saying that Israeli ideas were rejected
because they were in complete contradiction with the
U.S. withdrawal proposal.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli ideas were put forward by Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's adviser Yitzhak Molcho, who met with chief
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat for several hours on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting, the PNA officials had threatened the
session would be the last one unless Israel showed up with new
proposals.
</P>
<P>
Asfour did not say whether the Palestinians would carry out
their threat to break off the negotiations now.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior Palestinian source told Israel Radio that
during the talks, Israel agreed to grant PNA certain civil powers
in the proposed "nature reserve."
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians rejected the idea outright. The source
maintained that it was too early to say whether the Palestinians
agree to further meetings.
</P>
<P>
Israel has so far resisted a U.S. and Palestinian-backed plan
to give the Palestinians 13 percent more of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side is insisting that it will not accept the
Israeli proposal that 3 percent of that sum be called a "nature
reserve" with limitations on construction unless it is assured
that the area will receive the formal status of "Area B."
</P>
<P>
All Area B land is jointly controlled by Israel and the PNA in
an interim phase before becoming "Area A," which is exclusively
controlled by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Israeli diplomatic sources told Israel
Radio that they believe contacts with the Palestinians would be
renewed in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
They said that the ideas transferred by Molcho would allow for
progress in the negotiations if the Palestinians show good will.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
took a tour by air on the Judean desert area and examined
different possibilities for where the 3 percent of the further
redeployment designated for a "nature reserve" could be. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
