<HEADLINE> Arafat Rejects Israeli Latest Proposal on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH, WEST BANK, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat rejected Tuesday the latest
Israeli proposal on the second redeployment, saying it "had
nothing to do with" the U.S. initiative.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the remarks at a news conference after holding
near-two-hour talks with visiting Romanian Prime Minister Radu
Vasile in the West Bank town Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli proposal, put forward at the latest round of talks
between the Israelis and the Palestinians Monday night, was very
far from consistent with the U.S. initiative, Arafat said. He did
not elaborate on the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Israel has rejected the U.S. initiative which calls on Israel
to withdraw from an additional 13.1 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Palestinians will suspend talks with the Israelis
as they have threatened, Arafat said he and other Palestinian
officials were still considering the issue.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat met for several
hours with Yitzhak Molcho, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's adviser and the chief Israeli negotiator, on Monday
night. But neither would say after the meeting if enough progress
was made to keep the talks going.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials had threatened before the meeting that
it would be the last session unless the Israelis brought with
them new proposals.
</P>
<P>
Arafat was said to meet with Erekat and other Palestinian
negotiators in Gaza after the talks to hear their report.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Tuesday that Molcho proposed some "new
ideas" in the talks but it did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have opposed the Israeli idea that 3 percent
of the 13.1 percent due to be handed over to them by Israel be
designated as a "nature reserve" where the Palestinians will only
have limited powers.
</P>
<P>
Vasile said he visited Ramallah in an effort to promote
Romanian-Palestinian ties and to help advance the stalled peace
process. The prime minister, who arrived in Israel Sunday, held
talks with his Israeli counterpart Netanyahu Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
