<HEADLINE> Japan-China Trade Drops in First Half of 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Two-way trade between Japan and China
fell 7.9 percent in the first six months of 1998 from a year earlier to
27.53 billion dollars, marking the first decline during the
January-June period since 1990, a Japanese trade organization said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports to China amounted to 9.69 billion dollars, down 1.9
percent, while imports from China dropped 10.9 percent to 17.83
billion dollars, the Japan External Trade Organization (JETRO) said.
</P>
<P>
China was the fourth largest market for Japan's exports during the
six months, moving up from fifth place in the same period last year,
and remained the second biggest exporter to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Overall, China is Japan's second largest trading partner, following
the United States, it said.
</P>
<P>
The semigovernmental trade orgainzation predicted that bilateral
trade between the two countries for the whole year would fall just
below 60 billion dollars, down from the 63.8 billion dollars
registered in the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
