<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Level Rising in Upper, Middle Reaches of Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The water level in the upper and
middle reaches of the Yangtze River has been rising because of
persistent rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The Shishou hydrological station in central China's Hubei
Province recorded the water level at 39.97 meters at 8 a.m. today,
eight centimeters higher than the historic high of 1954.
</P>
<P>
The water level monitored at Chenglingji hydrological station
on Dongting Lake was 35.2 meters by 2 p.m. today, the same level
as Monday. The water level at the Hukou hydrological station of
Poyang Lake dropped to 22.47 meters at 2 p.m., a 0.04 meter drop
from Monday.
</P>
<P>
Poyang Lake and the lower reaches of the Yangtze are expecting
a new round of rainfall as this year's second strong tropical
storm is due to arrive in Jiangxi and Anhui provinces via Fujian
Province on Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Information from the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters disclosed that flooding also occurred on the Huaihe
River north of the Yangtze River, with the water level monitored
at Wangjiaba hydrological station climbing to 25.85 meters at 6
a.m. today. The water level is expected to rise to 28 meters by 6
p.m. Wednesday, 1.5 meters above the danger line.
</P>
<P>
Flooding in northeast China has continued. The water level in
the main stream of the Songhua River recorded at Xiadaiji
hydrological station was 99.15 meters at 8 a.m. today, 0.9 meters
above the danger line.
</P>
<P>
The water level in the main stream of the Nenjiang River
recorded at Dalai hydrological station dropped to 130.07 meters,
one centimeter lower than Monday but still 0.39 meters above the
safety line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
