<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Earnings in Zambia to Plummet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's export earnings this
year are forecast to go down from last year's 1,159 million U.S.
dollars to a mere 888 million dollars due to the declining
earnings from copper and non-taditional exports.
</P>
<P>
as a result, the country's current account deficit is also
expected to deteriorate further to 602 million dollars as against
235.1 million dollars last year, weekly Financial Mail reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a recent Economists Intelligent Unit country
report on Zambia and Congo (Kinshasa) as saying that copper
prices are expected to further decline in 1998 and 1999 primarily
because of weak demand in Asia.
</P>
<P>
While non-traditional exports are expected to record growth in
1998, this will not be enough to offset the expected fall in
revenue from copper, Zambia's largest foreign exchange earner,
resulting from declining production and slump in prices.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the drop in export earnings will
overshadow the drop in imports and thus contribute to the
widening current account deficit this year.
</P>
<P>
The situation is likely to adversely affect industry and
consumers as production costs for firms using imported raw
materials will rise and this could lead to increasing consumer
prices, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Terms Egypt's Privatization as Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) spoke highly of Egypt's privatization program, terming it "a
remarkable success story."
</P>
<P>
The comment was contained in IMF's latest report assessing
Egypt's economic performance since the reform drive started in
January 1996, the Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The pace of privatization that has been established compares
very favorably with recent international experience," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"The private sector's role has been increasing in virtually
every sector since 1996, with relatively large increases in
participation in industry, mining, construction, trade and
finance," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt's current privatization effort ranks among the top four
countries. Its privatization rate of about 1.5 percent of (gross
domestic product) GDP a year, is bettered only by Hungary,
Malaysia and the Czech Republic," it said.
</P>
<P>
On its reform agenda, the government's central objective is to
increase the real growth, with a greater role for private sector
in economic activities.
</P>
<P>
The reform program envisages a shrink in the size of civil
service by 2 percent a year, privatization of nonfinancial
enterprises to decrease public sector's role by 25 percent, and
conversion half of state- and jointly-owned banks to the control
of private sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform drive, private sector was also invited to
invest in new infrastructure projects, such as the building of
power plants, airports and port facilities, in the form of the
build-operate-transfer (BOT).
</P>
<P>
So far, 84 public companies have been sold with a market value
of about 17.7 billion pounds (5.21 billion U.S. dollars),
accounting for about 7 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
And from January 1996 to the end of June 1997, the government
earned 5.2 billion pounds (1.53 billion dollars) from
privatization, with 40 percent of the money paying off debts owing
to banks, 55 percent to treasury and five percent as early
retirement pensions.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to sell 200 companies by the year 2000
either "in full or in part." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
