<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Must Not Be Misused: Habibie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
Tuesday said that foreign assistance must not be misused as the
loans reflected international confidence in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We must use foreign assistance carefully," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) agreed recently in
Paris to aid Indonesia with 7.894 billion U.S. dollars in addition
to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) loan totaling 6.3 billion
dollars. The foreign loans are scheduled to be disbursed in fiscal
year 1998/99.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said he was also happy that the People's Republic of
China had also extended financial aid to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Indonesian cooking oil producers here, the
head of state said he expected the national economy to recover in
September 1999 if various foreign loans were used in the right
way.
</P>
<P>
The government had made many plans to restore the national
economy's health but the support of all sides, including the
public and the bureaucracy itself, was needed to enable these
plans to succeed, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody should disturb the implementation of these plans,"
Habibie stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
