<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Switzerland Offers Aid to S. African Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Switzerland has decided to
offer 16 million Rand (about 2.5 million U.S. Dollars) to aid
South African students.
</P>
<P>
An agreement, signed Monday by visiting Swiss President Flavio
Cotti and South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo, aims to
enable the South African government to establish the National
Student Financial Aid Scheme for needy students.
</P>
<P>
Cotti, who doubles the Swiss foreign minister, and Nzo also
signed a declaration of intent on joint action and projects on
issues of common interest, the daily Sowetan reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela was present at the
signing ceremony. Mandela had a 40-minute talk with Cotti
following the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Cotti kicked off his official visit to South Africa on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland is the fifth largest investor in South Africa and
the two countries are looking at further improving their good
relations, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
