<HEADLINE> Protests Force Change of Venue for Russian-U.S. Naval Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Protracted protests have forced
Russia and the United States to change the venue of a joint naval
exercise in Vladivostok in the Far East, a Russian officer said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nikolai Temerev, the Russian commander of the games, told a
news conference that the exercises, scheduled for August 6-7, will
be held in a different part of Primorye due to protests.
</P>
<P>
The new venue is a test site of the Pacific fleet in Clerk
islands, in the southeast of Amur Bay, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the exercises is to practice cooperation in
emergency situations, such as landing in a disaster-hit zone,
first-aid and evacuation of victims.
</P>
<P>
Local protesters picketed the naval pier of Vladivostok during
the mooring of the U.S. Germanytown landing ship for two hours.
About 50 people carrying red flags and banners chanted "Yankee go
home" and "Shame".
</P>
<P>
About 600 U.S. troops will take part in the exercises,
including a logistics group, units of the 31st Marine Corps, the
First Air Squadron and the Third Marine Division, Interfax quoted
the U.S. consulate in Vladivostok as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Russian side, also consisting of some 600 people, includes
the Burny destroyer, the BDK-11 landing ship and five auxiliary
vessels.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Germantown landing ship will remain in Vladivostok
until August 10.
</P>
<P>
Despite the change of venue, the protesters, backed by the
Primorye Territory governor and the speaker of the local
legislative assembly, said they would continue to voice their
opposition to the exercises "in every way", the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
