<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democratic Congo's Foreign Minister in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Bizima Karaha, was in South
Africa but had not contacted his diplomatic mission in Pretoria,
a DRC embassy official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Karaha was in South Africa, but had not contacted the mission
or local authorities, South African Press Association (SAPA)
quoted the DRC embassy official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Karaha failed to return home last Saturday, apparently after a
visit to Mozambique, leading to speculation that he was linked to
the tension in the DRC and was seeking asylum in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, at a briefing in Cape Town Tuesday, South African
Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi said that he was not
aware of any application for asylum by Karaha or any other DRC
officials as rumored in the media.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that DRC President Kabila had earlier ordered
all Rwandan soldiers who helped him overthrow former president
Mobutu Sese Seko to leave the country, sparking the tension.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
