<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vajpayee: India Wants to Improve Ties With China, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee said Tuesday that his country wanted to further
improve relations with China which he said his government had
never termed as India's biggest enemy.
</P>
<P>
During a debate on foreign policy Tuesday in Lok Sabha, the
lower house of Parliament, Vajpayee said that India stood for
intensifying its efforts to resolve outstanding border issues with
China.
</P>
<P>
The Indian prime minister said that the talks between his
special emissary Jaswant Singh and Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan in Manila recently had helped untie knots in bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said that his country was engaged in talks with key
nations on making its moratorium on further nuclear tests
internationally binding with a view to arriving at a decision
regarding adherence to the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
However, Vajpayee assured the Parliament that it would be taken
into confidence before signing any international treaty.
</P>
<P>
Marking a shift from his earlier stand that India was prepared
to discuss adherence to only certain provisions of the CTBT,
Vajpayee indicated Tuesday in the Upper House that New Delhi was
willing to consider the CTBT.
</P>
<P>
the prime minister said New Delhi had been undertaking
dialogues with key interlocutors after satisfying itself that
India no longer required to conduct nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"We can maintain the credibility of our nuclear deterrent in
the future without testing," he said. "India remains committed to
this dialogue with a view to arriving at a decision regarding to
adherence to the CTBT."
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee accused Pakistan of showing no interest in continuing
the bilateral talks for resolving outstanding issues between the
two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Squarely blaming Islamabad for attempting to internationalize
the Kashmir issue, he said that Pakistan was making Kashmir its
focal point in running its diplomacy while ignoring other vital
issues of trade and economy.
</P>
<P>
Asserting that Kashmir was an integral part of India, Vajpayee
once again ruled out any third party mediation in the
Indo-Pakistani dispute over Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Saying that attempts by Pakistan to make Kashmir a flash point
would not succeed, Vajpayee rejected Islamabad's demand that New
Delhi should hold talks with the Hurriyat Conference, a
conglomerate of separatist bodies.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan is not happy with its present borders and
wants to change the status quo, adding that even Arab countries
had not supported Pakistani move to internationalize the Kashmir
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mogadishu Quiet After Announcement of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Mogadishu is quiet Tuesday
despite political uncertainty in the wake of the announcement of
the capital's long-awaited administration at the absence of
faction leader Osman Ali Atto late Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that an administration of any form was
established for Mogadishu since the chaos began in the capital in
early 1991.
</P>
<P>
Atto dismissed the administration announced by Ali Mahdi,
Hussein Aidid and Mohamed Qanyare Afrah with his interior
secretary Colonel Abdi Hassan Awale Qeybdid, saying that he
didn't recognize the co-chairmanship of Ali Mahdi and Hussein
Aidi for the supreme council of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The faction leader also made an appeal to the public as well
as to the international community not to recognize this
administration which he called as unlawful.
</P>
<P>
He said the center of the conflict between him and the
administration announcers is the way the constitution is formed
and who will have the final word and sign the approval of the
administration.
</P>
<P>
The faction leader characterized the administration as
non-representative. His message to the public which was also run
on his radio Monday night has warned that those who announced
this administration alone will shoulder the responsibility of its
consequences.
</P>
<P>
Atto declined to make clear whether he will fight the group or
not. But he said that he is holding another meeting with all
those who rejected this administration including Musa Sudi
Yalahow and Dr Hussein Bod's representatives, to formulate what
he called the convenient way of establishing Mogadishu's
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The people of the capital have long been looking forward to
hearing and seeing an effective administration for Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
However, despite many stumbling blocks, the analysts are
ruling out the possibility of a major breakout of armed clashes
between the various political rivals in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Among those other influential leaders who also oppose to this
administration is general Mohamed Sheikh Osman, the former
finance minister of the late regime.
</P>
<P>
He characterized the administration as a non-democratic and
aimed at hijacking the peace process in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
General Osman who is a clan compatriot has warned against any
armed clashes between the various groups of the capital.
</P>
<P>
In Monday's speeches at Hussein Aidid's headquarters at the
presence of Egyptian and Libyan diplomats including Al-Sayid
Ma'tuq Al-Zubaidi, the Libyan ambassador to Somalia, the faction
leaders have also announced that the air and sea ports are open
from Tuesday on.
</P>
<P>
However, there has been no sign of activities around the two
main installations despite the nomination of their general
managers.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of people have gone to the air and sea ports Tuesday to
see if there are any changes.
</P>
<P>
However, neither the airport nor the seaport can be opened
without the basic equipments to run them such as tag boats,
cranes, large electric generators, air tower communications,
refueling system for the planes and descending stairs for the
large planes, and etc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0106 </DOCNO>
