<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Government Gets Tough on Citizenship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian federal government
has begun going to court to overturn judges' decisions granting
citizenship to immigrants who spend little time in Canada, the
Globe and Mail newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government is reviewing any case in which a judge granted
citizenship to an immigrant who spends more than 50 percent of his
time living abroad, and filing appeals to the court over certain
cases.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year, the Department of Citizenship
and Immigration has taken 61 such cases before the Federal Court.
Five of these have been heard, with four being decided in the
government's favor.
</P>
<P>
Many of the cases have to do with immigrants from Hong Kong who
established residence in Canada and then returned to Hong Kong for
prolonged periods for business or other reasons.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Citizenship Act says that an immigrant must spend at
least three years (1,095 days) out of four within Canada to
qualify. The purpose of the residence requirement is to ensure
that an applicant can become familiar with Canada and become
integrated into Canadian society.
</P>
<P>
Physical presence is not defined under the act. However, case
law establishes that applicants can be absent and still qualify
under exceptional circumstances if, for example, the absences are
temporary and caused by business or study. During these absences,
the applicant and immediate family are required to maintain a
residence in Canada and pay income taxes here.
</P>
<P>
Citizenship registrar Norman Sabourin said the purpose of the
residence requirement is to make sure prospective citizens learn
about Canadian society, its values and laws.
</P>
<P>
If a person spends too much time outside Canada, he said, the
intent of the Citizenship Act is defeated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Earmarks $47 Million for Vaccines to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
earmarked four billion Naira (about 47 million U.S. Dollars) for
the local production of vaccine to eradicate childhood diseases
in the country.
</P>
<P>
A report from Tuesday's New Nigerian quoted Alhaji Tukur Mani,
permanent secretary of Nigerian Health Ministry, as saying this
was part of the federal government's efforts to provide good
health care delivery system for its citizens.
</P>
<P>
He told a media briefing Monday to mark 1998 National
Immunization Day that his government had embarked on various
projects on immunization to set the country free from diseases
that are preventable.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the efforts made by the Federal Government, he
said, the west African country still ranked among the three
countries yet to eradicate poliomyelitis.
</P>
<P>
At present, Mani noted, "immunization coverage for the target
diseases is low, surveillance remains poor and completeness of
reporting is estimated at 55 percent."
</P>
<P>
The health official disclosed that his government had devised
and implemented strategies toward improving the immunization
coverage in the country.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Mary Awosika, the national coordinator
and chief executive officer of NPI Management Board, said the
objective of the board was to develop and promote programs geared
toward reducing childhood mortality and morbidity through
adequate immunization coverage for all children under five years
old and pregnant women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
