<HEADLINE> China Calls Out More People to Combat Flooding on Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 2.26 million Chinese
civilians and soldiers are being mobilized today to protect
embankments along the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze
River, an increase of 70,000 people from Monday.
</P>
<P>
The information from the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters said People's Liberation Army soldiers and Armed
Police men make up 35,000 of the workforce.
</P>
<P>
Dangerous situations had been reported in 3,530 places on the
embankments built along the main stream of the Yangtze River since
flooding first occurred on the river in late June.
</P>
<P>
By August 2 the headquarters had shipped a large number of goods
and materials used for combating floods to provinces along the
middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River and to provinces
bordering the Nenjiang River in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The five provinces of Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi, Anhui and Jiangsu
on the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze have also spent a
total of 2.495 billion yuan for flood-related work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
