<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Moves to Tap Overseas Oil Construction Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China is actively exploring
international oil construction markets, along with consistent
efforts to tap huge oil and gas resources domestically by inviting
foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
In coming years, China is expected to develop transnational oil
production focusing on the Middle East, Russia, Central Asia and
other countries and regions rich in oil, according to Qin Anmin,
president of the China Petroleum Engineering Construction
Enterprise Group (CPECEG).
</P>
<P>
Qin said that China plans to turn out 10 million tons of crude
oil through its overseas production by the turn of the
century. And by 2010 China will try to develop an annual overseas
oil capacity of 20 million tons, in addition to an annual gas
supply of 50 billion cubic meters, he said.
</P>
<P>
Presently, China is reporting headway in oil exploration and
development overseas. The China National Petroleum Corp. (CNPC)
and its subsidiary China Petroleum Engineering Construction Corp.
(CPECC) have successfully obtained share-holding, operational and
leasing rights for oil fields in such countries as Peru, Canada,
Thailand and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China is enjoying great prospects in its oil and gas
exploration in Iraq, the Sudan and Russia. A cooperative gas
project in Central Asia is expected to provide China with 25
billion cubic meters of gas a year. Under the agreement, China
will build a long-distance gas pipeline running from the area
through China, Japan and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
In line with a Sino-Russian cooperative gas project, China will
build another long-distance gas pipeline in eastern Siberia which
will help supply China with an expected 25 billion cubic meters of
gas a year.
</P>
<P>
According to Qin, China has made marked progress in undertaking
oil projects overseas. The CPECC has so far signed overseas oil
construction contracts worth 1.67 billion U.S. dollars. It has
been listed among the world's top 225 contractors for five
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
The official said China is rich in oil resources, producing
more than 150 million tons of crude oil annually and having so far
verified total oil deposits of 17 billion tons, ranking 5th and
9th, respectively, in the world.
</P>
<P>
Qin said China's petroleum development strategy is to rely
mainly on domestic resources, speed up Sino-foreign cooperation in
exploring the western and offshore oil and gas resources, and step
up efforts to tap international oil markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Cautions Against Exaggerating Tension with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Richard Butler, chairman of the
U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM,
cautioned Tuesday against exaggerating the tension after the
collapse of his talks with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Before departing for Bahrain, the U.N. chief weapons inspector
said he would not use the word "crisis" to describe the relations
between the UNSCOM and Iraq after the latest talks.
</P>
<P>
"It's highly important not to exaggerate the situation," he was
quoted by the official Iraqi news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Butler and the UNSCOM delegation cut short their stay in
Baghdad Tuesday after their talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz on the progress in the U.N. inspection mission broke
down Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Butler said during the talks Aziz demanded him tell the
U.N. Security Council to give Iraq a clean bill of health on its
weapons programs, but he rejected the request citing the he had
no such evidence.
</P>
<P>
He said that the whole matter would be reported Thursday to the
U.N. Security Council when he returns to New York.
</P>
<P>
"I am certain that the (Security) Council will work to find a
solution and define what the next step should be," he added.
</P>
<P>
After Monday's talks, Aziz accused Butler of serving the
U.S. interest by attempting to prolong the inspection mission,
thus extending the crippling sanctions imposed by the U.N. after
the 1990 Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Aziz rejected Butler's proposal for creating a new plan of
action as "old tricks and games." 
</P>
</TEXT>
