<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Building Collapse Toll in Mumbai Rises to 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The toll in the building
collapse in Mumbai has risen to 22 as rescuers searched Tuesday
for the dead and survivors from debris of an apartment building
which crumbled to the ground Monday night in the Indian commercial
capital.
</P>
<P>
The Press Trust of India (PTI) reported from Mumbai that the
toll was expected to go up further as some inmates of the
seven-story Govind Towers were still missing and presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
The building, which collapsed around 20:05 local time Monday,
housed shops on the ground floor, residential apartments on the
first, second and third floors and a hotel on the upper three,
according to fire brigade sources.
</P>
<P>
Fire brigade personnel, making use of cranes, were busy in the
rescue operation. The clearing of the mountain of debris is
expected to continue till Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Residents said there was some unauthorized construction on the
top floor and they had complained to the municipality that the
15-year-old building had been tilting to one side for some months.
</P>
<P>
The police said, however, the civic authorities had served an
eviction notice to the residents, but they had stayed on
disregarding safety.
</P>
<P>
It was the first incident of building collapse in the
metropolis since the beginning of monsoon this year and the eighth
in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The National Herald daily said Tuesday that such incidents
have been a regular feature in the commercial capital of the
country during the last few years.
</P>
<P>
On the average, according to the daily, three to four buildings
collapse every year in Mumbai, killing scores of people.
</P>
<P>
Municipal authorities have become rather strict in granting
permission to build high-rise buildings in the metropolis due to
such unfortunate incidents, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
