<HEADLINE> Barmasai and Mutola Expected to Beat World Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Bernard Barmasai and Mozambique's
Maria Mutola are both hopeful to break world records at Wednesday night's
Stockholm IAAF Grand Prix meeting, meet director Rajne Soderberg said here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Barmasai will attempt to better his own mark of seven minutes 55.72 seconds
for the 3,000 meters steeplechase while Mutola is aiming to break the women's
800m mark of 1:53.28 set by Jarmila Kratochvilova of Czechoslovakia in Munich,
Germany, in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Barmasai, who set his own mark in Cologne almost 12 months ago, is tipped to
beat the record since his compatriot and world champion Wilson Boit Kipketer,
himself a former record holder at the distance, will also compete in the meet.
</P>
<P>
Stockholm is known as a venue where the 3,000m steeplsechase record can be
broken. Finland's Jouko Kuha (1968), Swede Anders Gaerderud (1975) and Kenyan
Peter Koech (1989) have all set records at the venue.
</P>
<P>
Russian Lyubov Gurina and Letitia Vriesde (Surinam), along with Morocco's
Hasna Benhassi will also join Mutola in the women's 800 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
