<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over Half Lebanese Oppose Longer President's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A public opinion poll published
Tuesday showed that 56 percent of the Lebanese opposed the
extension of President Elias Hrawi's term.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by Lebanese pollster "Stat Ipsos", came
less than two months before the parliament elects the new
president.
</P>
<P>
Among the 1,000 polled, who came from all walks of life, 43
percent still believed that Hrawi was likely to be granted another
extension, while 42 percent said it was impossible.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi, 72, a Maronite Christian, was elected president in
October 1989 with strong Syrian backing.
</P>
<P>
While his first six-year term expired in 1995, the parliament
voted to approve an one-time constitutional amendment, allowing
him to stay on for an extra three and half years.
</P>
<P>
According to Lebanon's constitution, the country's top political
posts are equally shared by Muslims and Christians.
</P>
<P>
The president comes from Maronite Christians, the prime
minister from Sunni Muslims, the house speaker from Shiite
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Presidential candidates have not yet been identified, but the
survey listed 15 Maronite political figures whom it said were
possible contenders.
</P>
<P>
The most favored candidate was Army Commander Emile Lahoud, who
garnered 30 percent support among the surveyed.
</P>
<P>
Local observers predicted Tuesday that Hrawi would visit Syria
soon to discuss with his Syrian counterpart Hafez Assad the
upcoming presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has great influence on Lebanon, is believed to
play a decisive role in Lebanon's presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
