<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Professors to Receive High Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China will select 300-to-500
professors to receive a special subsidy of 100,000 yuan (12,000
U.S. dollars) every year.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest payment a Chinese teacher is expected to
get from the government. An ordinary university professor's
monthly salary is about 2,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The special subsidy will be an additional award and not include
the salaries and welfare these professors normally receive.
</P>
<P>
These professors must be leading figures in their fields, a
spokesman for the Ministry of Education announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The program, known as "Project Yangtze," is aimed at easing the
problem of a shortage of talented young scholars in the country.
</P>
<P>
Most leading scholars are expected to retire around 2000 which
will leave an academic vacuum caused by the "Cultural Revolution"
20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials say they hope the program will help increase
Chinese academia's competitiveness and create a group of
world-renowned masters.
</P>
<P>
In another bid to encourage academics, Ka-shing Li, a famous
Hong Kong entrepreneur, will establish a foundation to award some
of the top-achieving professors. The top award will be 1 million
yuan (120,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
These special professors will be employed from China and
abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
