<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Lt. Gen. Stripped From Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Lt. Gen. Prabowo
Subianto has been removed from his post as head of the Indonesian
Armed Forces (ABRI) Staff and Command School, Antara News Agency
Tuesday quoted a reliable source as saying.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo has not been reassigned to any other position as of
August 1, according to the source who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The ABRI High Command also stripped Maj. Gen. Muchdi
Purwopranjoyo of his job as ABRI's deputy inspector general, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
Both men were once commander of the Army's Special Forces unit
(Kopassus), a number of whose members are currently in military
police custody on suspicion of being involved in the abduction and
torture of scores of students and other political activists prior
to Soeharto's election to his 7th term as the country's head of
state and government last March.
</P>
<P>
After obtaining increasing clues about both men's roles in the
political abductions, ABRI Commander Gen. Wiranto signed the
decisions discharging the two from their official posts on July
31, the source said.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here Monday, Wiranto said Prabowo, Muchdi
and Kopassus's Group IV (intelligence) commander Col. Chairawan
would appear before the Officers Honorary Council, headed by Army
chief of staff Gen. Subagyo.
</P>
<P>
There are indications that the three officers have broken the
military code of ethics and have shown a lack of discipline in
performing their duties, Wiranto said, adding that 10 Kopassus
soldiers ranking below colonel will soon face a military tribunal
to answer charges they had been actively involved in the
abductions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
