<HEADLINE> S. Korean FM Resigns Over Diplomatic Row With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Foreign Minister Park
Chung-soo resigned on Tuesday to take responsibility for the
recent diplomatic row with Russia, a presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Dae-jung has accepted Park's resignation and on
Wednesday named current Ambassador-at-large Hong Soon-young as a
replacer, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The resignation came after Park was blamed at home for the
strained S. Korean-Russian relations stemmed from the diplomatic
row between the two nations starting last month.
</P>
<P>
On July 4, Russia ordered the expulsion of a South Korean
diplomat, Cho Sung-woo, on spy charges. Four days later, South
Korea retaliated by ordering the expulsion of a Russian diplomat
in Seoul, Oleg N. Abramkin.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks later South Korea further agreed to withdraw five
more intelligence agents in Russia in line with the level of
Russian agents in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Hong, 61, was a former deputy foreign minister and
ex-ambassador to Moscow. His appointment is seen here as a move
aimed to patch up the tense bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
