<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Maintain Order in Flooded Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANXIANG, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese police are stepping up
efforts to crack down on crime in flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
"Cases such as looting, robbery and stealing are on the rise,
as troublemakers are taking advantage of the severe flooding,"
said Li Weihe, director of the Public Security Bureau of Anxiang
County, central China's Hunan Province, which has been
experiencing its worst flooding in more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
"Through intensified efforts of local police, the situation is
getting better," said Li, who has been at his post for more than a
month.
</P>
<P>
On the night of July 24, when huge floods on the Yangtze River
engulfed more than 20,000 hectares of land in the county, many
local farmers were so helpless that they just left their precious
belongings on roofs and trees.
</P>
<P>
"In the beginning of the flooding, when night fell some
hooligans took boats to get things out of the water -- some even
went into rooms to plunder," he said.
</P>
<P>
This immediately put local police on the alert. On July 29, Guo
Zebao of Dexing Village was caught stealing pigs and electrical
appliances from a semi-submerged building.
</P>
<P>
Between July 26 and 30, six groups of more than 30 thieves were
seized. The number of offenses have been markedly reduced since
August, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has set up 16 police duty points along the
60-kilometer embankment, where the flood victims have been living
for 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has also organized police-civilian defense squads to
conduct round-the-clock patrols on the river, and reinforced
safety efforts for financial, post and telecommunications, and
power departments.
</P>
<P>
Some 100,000 people have been staying on the levee, but no
massive riots or scrambles for relief supplies have taken place,
Li said, adding that the police will keep a close watch on such
cases until all displaced persons have been resettled.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
