<HEADLINE> Philippine President Advocates Use of Native Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Tuesday called on all public officials and employees to
start using Filipino in their official discussions and
negotiations to gain a headstart in propagating the national
language.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he ordered the Department of Education, Culture and
Sports and the Commission on Higher Education to start using
Filipino as the mode of teaching in all state universities and
public schools.
</P>
<P>
"Let's not cite the effects of globalization and the
information revolution as excuses to suppress the propagation of
our national language," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He said Filipinos should feel proud in speaking their national
language and should devote each day to encourage its widespread
use.
</P>
<P>
He advised government officials comfortable with speaking
English to start learning fluent Filipino, stressing that under
his administration, the use of the national language mandated by
the Constitution will be strictly followed.
</P>
<P>
"I want our Cabinet officials to be fluent and excellent in
speaking our national language not because I don't know how to
speak English but because most of them don't know how to speak
Filipino. How will they talk to ordinary citizens if they speak
English? We should lead by example," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the use of Filipino as the national language
would serve as the foundation for Filipinos to strengthen their
unity and defend their race, culture, history and destiny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
