<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke080447 -250,000 Int'l Passengers Transported by Air in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 250,000 foreign passengers
were transported by Myanmar's international airline and 11 other
foreign airlines in the 1997-98 fiscal year ending in March,
according to a latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Airways International, a joint venture airline
between state-run domestic Myanmar Airways and the Highsonic
Enterprise Private LTD of Singapore established in 1993, has been
flying externally with Boeing 737-400 aircraft, leased from the
Malaysian Airlines System, to seven destinations covering Bangkok,
Hong Kong, Dhaka, Kuala Lumpur, Singapore, Kunming and Jakarta,
and bringing back a considerable number of international
passengers.
</P>
<P>
Other foreign airlines that have regular flights to Yangon from
their respective capitals include Biman (Bangladesh), Royal Brunei
 Airlines, Air China, Druk Air (Bhutan), Indian Airlines, Lao
Aviation Co, All Nippon Airways (Japan), Malaysian Airlines
System, Pakistan International Airways, Silk Air (Singapore) and
Thai Airways International.
</P>
<P>
In early 1997, Myanmar and Indonesia signed a memorandum of
understanding on setting up of a joint venture to run domestic
services in the country with a plan to buy aircraft from the PT.
Triputra Unggul Utama Co of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, a Canadian helicopter company also reached an
agreement later in the year with the Myanmar Airways to form a
joint venture helicopter international company to transport
passengers domestically.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, a total of 900,000 passengers were
transported on the domestic routes in the 1997-98 by the state-run
Myanmar Airways and other joint venture airlines such as Air
Mandalay and Yangon Airways which have extended their flights to
Thailand's border towns of Chiangmai and Phuket.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Airways is operating its internal flight services
with a fleet of seven Fokker F-27 and three Fokker F-28 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some Thai airlines have also been allowed to operate
direct chartered flights since the end of 1993 to Myanmar's
tourist sites Mandalay, Bagan, Tachilek, kengtung and Heho.
</P>
<P>
Another Japanese airline, the JAL, also initiated chartered
flight to Yangon from Fukuoka in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
Despite Myanmar opened more air links with a number of foreign
countries in 1996 when the country launched a tourist year
campaign, the country received a smaller number of tourists in the
past two years. The country is taking measures to attract tourists
in the forthcoming tourist season beginning October.
</P>
<P>
Development works for Yangon International Airport is being
undertaken, while construction of new Hanthawaddy International
Airport in Bago division, 80 kilometers away from Yangon, and
Mandalay International Airport, 680 km from the capital, is also
being carried out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
