<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 27 Sierra Leonean Rebels Surrender to ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-seven rebels loyal to the
outsted Sierra Leonean military junta of Johnny Paul Koromah,
surrendered to the west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG Monday
in Kenema, east Sierra Leone, media reports said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Koromah's men surrendered to the ECOMOG
since Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah granted amnesty
to the rebels last months, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ECOMOG Force Commander, Major-General Timothy
Shelpidi has said that his force will be able to flush out the
rebels as soon as support promised by the international community
arrives.
</P>
<P>
Shelpidi told a U.N. conference in New York at the weekend
that what ECOMOG needs more logistic support, troops and an end
to illegal supplies to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
He said that flushing the rebels out of Sierra Leone will take
more time than people expected because the rebels now operate in
a terrain where is thickly forested and mountainous and has been
their base since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have resorted to guerrilla type of tactics,
destroying bridges and creating caters, thus slowing down the
movement of ECOMOG, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shelpidi also said that ECOMOG has ample evidence to show that
former fighters of Liberian President Charles Taylor have been
fighting alongside the rebels and providing them with supplies.
</P>
<P>
Once the rebels have no resupplies, they would have nothing to
fight with and would have no food and so would have to give up,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Shelpidi expressed the hope that the decisions taken at a
recent mini-summit in Nigeria by leaders of Nigeria, Sierra Leone
and Liberia will end the supply of arms, ammunition and other
logistics to the rebels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
