<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Stock Market Slides Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices Slided lower on
Singapore Market Tuesday due to sharp fall on Wall Street and the
bleak outlook on the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index (STII) lost 9.77
points to close at 1,064.99 points.
</P>
<P>
The total volume was 98.33 million shares worth 189.23 million
Singapore dollars (about 115.70 million U.S. dollars). There were
137 losers against 110 gainers while 340 counters remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
ST Cap was the most active stock as it registered a turnover of
8.81 million units. It was followed by TAC 200 that ended on a
turnover of 7.67 million counters. DBS F was next with 4.02
million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
GE Life was the top gainer of the day as it gained 30 cents to
close at 9.30 Singapore dollars. UOB F edged up 25 cents to 5.40
Singapore dollars at close. OUB F was up 24 cents to finish at
3.46 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser as it lost
20 cents to close at 21.40 Singapore dollars. Shangri shed 14
cents to end at 1.94 Singapore dollars. S inched down 12 cents to
finish at 4.40 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said share prices fell slightly in the morning session
but the last-minute selling in index-linked stocks drove the STII
index lower toward the close.
</P>
<P>
The fall was a reflection to a sharp drop on Wall Street and
gloom prospect of the Singapore's Economy, they said.
</P>
<P>
They said investors remain on the sidelines and wait for
companies to unveil their financial results within the next few
weeks to evaluate the impact of the regional economic and
financial woes on bottomlines.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also said institutional buying in bank shares placed
them among the top gainers as investors are starting to think
banks having weathered the Asian financial turmoil better.
</P>
</TEXT>
