<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Halt Stockpile Wool Sales for 11 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government Tuesday announced a freeze on all sales from the
nation's wool stockpile for the rest of the 1998-99 season in a
bid to spur on low prices.
</P>
<P>
Australian Primary Industries Minister John Anderson said this
pause would provide an opportunity for the wool industry and the
government to take stock of the market situation and future likely
developments in textile and clothing industries around the world.
</P>
<P>
Under the move, the Australian government will legislate for a
freeze on all sales of wool from the country's 1.1-million-bale
stockpile for the remainder of the season, which started on July
1.
</P>
<P>
The decision, reached Tuesday by federal cabinet, would provide
relief for wool growers in the short-term by removing a
substantial volume of wool from the market, the minister said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The low prices were caused by weak demands from Australia's
major wool markets in Asia, which has been hard hit by the current
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said a major assessment of the world wool and textile
industry would form the basis for a future decision on future
stockpile management beyond June, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
