<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
recovered from an early slide to close stronger Tuesday, thanks to
a 3.43 percent gain by market heavyweight BHP and a stronger
dollar.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished the day 8.5 points
firmer at 2682.3.
</P>
<P>
Ord Minnett client adviser Don Chandler said Australia's
leading company BHP's 45.8-Australian-cent surge to close at 13.82
Australian dollars would have "added a couple of points" to the
local index.
</P>
<P>
The market continues to respond positively to Monday's
much-anticipated announcement that National Australia Bank
Managing Director Don Argus would succeed Jerry Ellis as BHP
chairman next year.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 60.58 U.S. cents, up from
60.36 U.S. cents late Monday.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian equities market, the all industrials index
closed 3.5 up at 4726.5, while the all resources index added 14.5
to 1030.4.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the financial sector, the four biggest Australian
banks had a mixed day, with the banking index dipping 3.5 points
to 5963.8.
</P>
<P>
The ANZ bank shed 18 cents to 10.45 Australian dollars,
National Australia Bank fell five cents to 22.49 Australian
dollars, while the Commonwealth Bank of Australia added 13 cents
to 20.45 Australian dollars and the Westpac bank found five cents
to 10.42 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among resources stock, Rio Tinto rose 28 cents to 18.50
Australian dollars, with ongoing speculation about the
Ango-Australian mining giant's interest in BHP's mineral division
helping to fuel the gain.
</P>
<P>
The gold index increased 0.2 points to 1027.1, in line with a
softening in the price of the precious metal.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney in afternoon trade was
285.40 U.S. dollars an ounce, down from Monday's 286.55 U.S.
dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 292.53 million shares worth 297.48
million U.S. dollars, with falling stocks outnumbering rising
stocks by 551 to 439. 
</P>
</TEXT>
