<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Make Renewable Energy Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will
soon declare a renewable energy policy to give the solar, wind,
biomass, thermal, wave and tidal energy sources a commercial
dimension, The Financial Express daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Commerce and Industries Minister Tofael
Ahmed while addressing a meeting here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The government has been encouraging private investment in
renewable energy sector," the minister said, adding that an
attractive package of incentives to the investors in the sector
would be offered in the national policy.
</P>
<P>
The renewable energy could be easily be used for rural
electrification and poverty alleviation, and the diversification
of energy sources would have national and social implications, he
stated.
</P>
<P>
The government has planned to increase the electricity
generation capacity by at least 1,000 mw from the available power
capacity of 1,900-2,000 mw at present in order to meet the
ever-increasing demand for electricity.
</P>
<P>
Though the country was producing renewable energy in large
scale, the other sources of renewable energy still remained
untapped, he observed.
</P>
<P>
A solar photovoltaic pilot project with a generation capacity
of 62 kw is being implemented by the Rural Electrification Board
with French financial and technical assistance, he told the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government had also floated a tender for
implementation of a waste energy project in Dhaka on BOO (build,
own and operate) basis, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
