<HEADLINE> State Emergency Declared Islandwide in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Parliament Speaker
K.B. Ratnayake Tuesday announced that the state of emergency has
been extended Islandwide with effect from Monday midnight.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the emergency which carried out in 1994, has been
operative only in the country's north and east where Tamil rebels
are fighting against government troops for a separate Tamil state.
</P>
<P>
The move to impose emergency laws Islandwide was aimed at
postponing Provincial Council Elections (PCE) because the main
opposition United National party had refused the amend laws to
delay the vote which is due on August 28, informed sources here
said.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government had earlier said it was in no
position to provide security for the PCE because a large number of
troops and police had been deployed in the north of the country to
fight against the Tamil rebels.
</P>
<P>
But the Sri Lankan constitution doesn't allow the government to
delay the vote for the PCE, unless a state of emergency is
declared across the island country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
