<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Vows to Implement Administrative Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi pledged Tuesday to carry out administrative reform aimed at
reorganizing Japan's 22 government ministries and agencies into 13
entities by the year 2001, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
"The reform is one of the most crucial issues for the cabinet
and I will actively promote it. I am resolved to carry out the
reform," Obuchi was quoted as telling a meeting at the
government's administrative reform headquarters.
</P>
<P>
"There will be many difficulties with the work, but I would
like (cabinet members) to take a strong political leadership,"
Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi expressed his intention to realize "a visible
streamlining of bureaucracy" through deregulation, the transfer of
powers from the central government to local governments, and a
revision of roles of the government and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
As a part of the administrative reform, Obuchi has proposed
that the central government employees will be reduced by 20
percent over a 10-year period and costs will be cut by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Administrative reform, along with five other major reforms,
were proposed by former Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto. The law of Administrative reform went into effect in
June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
