<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Germany Sign Agricultural Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and Germany have signed an
agreement on enhancing bilateral agricultural cooperation, the
Daily Star newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed here on Monday, Germany will provide
Lebanon with technical aid in raising milk cows, protecting animal
health, and promoting livestock sciences and agricultural
mechanization.
</P>
<P>
Germany also promised to support Lebanon's agro-industrial
projects through the government-backed German Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank will offer loans to Lebanese farmers as well as
consultation services in the fields of planning and investment.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Minister of Agriculture Shawki Fakhoury said after the
signing ceremony that the agreement could be considered as an
alternative compensation for Lebanon's growing deficit in its
agricultural trade with Germany.
</P>
<P>
Fakhoury added that European countries refuse to buy Lebanon's
agricultural products because they are of the same variety.
</P>
<P>
This has prompted the country to sign identical agreements with
France and Bulgaria, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added that his country also planned to strike deals with
Spain, Ireland and other countries in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon imports an annual 3.5 billion U.S. dollars worth of
agricultural goods from European countries while its exports to
them stand at less than 150 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
