<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MOFTEC Issues Anti-Smuggling Circular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) today issued an urgent circular
to strengthen the management of foreign trade enterprises in a bid
to combat smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The circular required foreign trade administrations at all
levels to enhance the policy publicity and supervision for all
traders, including those foreign-funded ventures with trading
rights.
</P>
<P>
According to the circular, all traders are prohibited to permit
enterprises with no trading rights to sign import or export
contracts or conduct import and export businesses by using the
traders' names in transactions. All non-trading enterprises
affiliated with the trading companies should halt their
relationship immediately and stop their commercial activities, it
said.
</P>
<P>
As for import proxy, the circular banned the traders from
serving as agents with no knowledge of the real contents of the
imported goods, receivers, and foreign traders. Trading
enterprises are not allowed to serve as import agents for
companies claimed to fully handle their own customer affairs,
goods and custom procedures, it said. Smuggling which occurs in
such transactions will result in the punishment of traders as the
agents, the circular stressed.
</P>
<P>
Also, except for authorized state trading companies and
overseas-funded enterprises with trading rights, other trading
companies are not allowed to serve as import agents.
</P>
<P>
The circular urged relevant departments to strengthen the
management of the processing trade. All foreign trade
administrations should strictly check the processing contracts and
the processing capabilities of the enterprises in an effort to
prevent smuggling and other illegal activities in the name of
processing trade.
</P>
<P>
For the processing of sensitive commodities, the foreign trade
departments should strictly approve the volume of imported
materials and the duration of the processing, and oversee the
ensured sales of finished products, the circular said. Trading
management authorities should terminate the approval of processing
contracts for those involved in smuggling activities, it added.
</P>
<P>
The circular also requires all local foreign trade
administrations to strictly control the quota-license issuance and
prohibits the issuance of licenses beyond the quota or their
authorized scope. All trading companies are prohibited from
selling import and export licenses in the name of joint management
or proxy.
</P>
<P>
According to the circular, MOFTEC will warn, adjourn or
withdraw the import and export rights for violators. People
involved in the smuggling will be penalized in accordance with
relevant laws, it said.
</P>
<P>
The circular also requires foreign trade administrations at all
levels to actively cooperate with law enforcement organs, such as
the Customs houses, in their efforts to end smuggling and other
illegal activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
