<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ferature: Tibetan Rural Residents Eager for Knowledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- One rainy evening, Bazhub, Tibetan
headmaster of the evening school in Chazhub Village, had to teach
his students to write Tibetan letters by candlelight because of a
power failure.
</P>
<P>
His intense students were not young pupils, but adults who
are already parents.
</P>
<P>
The Chazhub evening school is one of 52 in Nedong County in the
Tibet Autonomous Region, and is located near the famous Chazhub
Temple at the foot of the Tongku Lhakang Monastery, the first
palace in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
To enable all adults under 45 years old to be able to read and
write by the end of the century, Nedong County has set up 162 free
classes for farmers and herdsmen. More than 2,300 people are now
attending these classes after work.
</P>
<P>
Memar, a thirty-year-old woman in the junior class at Chazhub
evening school, said she and her husband missed their chance to go
to school when they were young. Now they feel that even farm work
demands knowledge, so they attend the school for two hours every
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Her husband Dawa, 37, in the senior class next door, was
studying math. Giving quick answers to the questions, he put on a
proud look.
</P>
<P>
He said: "One month of study is very fruitful. After I graduate
from here, I needn't turn to asking others when I prepare the
pesticide."
</P>
<P>
An official of Nedong County said that at the end of the 1970s,
80 percent of all Tibetans in the county were illiterate. The
Tibetans now have come to realize that the major impediment to
economic growth is illiteracy among the people.
</P>
<P>
The campaign against illiteracy has been quite successful. By the
end of last year, the illiteracy rate in this county dropped to 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Schooling has made the Tibetans rich. Last year, the income per
capita in Nedong County reached 1,400 yuan, 40 percent higher than
the average for the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
