<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Delegation Leaves Baghdad After Collapse of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chief U.N. arms inspector Richard
Butler and his colleagues cut their trip short and left Baghdad
Tuesday morning after talks on dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction collapsed.
</P>
<P>
Neither Butler, chief of the U.N. Special Commission for
disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM, nor Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz gave specifics on what was discussed and what led to
the collapse of the talks held Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who had been scheduled to stay in Baghdad till
Wednesday, will be in New York Wednesday to brief the
U.N. Security Council on his trip to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
An informed U.N. source, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
told Xinhua that Aziz had told Butler he would not continue talks
with him.
</P>
<P>
When Butler asked Aziz whether his words meant that Iraq would
stop cooperation with the UNSCOM, which is in charge of destroying
Iraqi nuclear, chemical and biological weapons, Aziz replied "I
did not say that."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Monday night after the talks, Aziz said
Iraq was willing to continue cooperation, but it cannot work when
Butler was not ready to tell the truth to the Security Council
about the disarmament progress.
</P>
<P>
Aziz also said that he had rejected Butler's proposal for a
new plan of action, saying it made no sense when UNSCOM was
ignoring essential issues and focusing on minor and insignificant
ones to waste time.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Butler of serving the U.S. interests by
trying to prolong the crippling sanctions imposed by the
U.N. after the 1990 Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"Since this is the wish of the American administration to
perpetuate the situation, to prolong the current situation, to
keep the sanctions on the people of Iraq. ... as long as this is
the American wish, you (Butler) are serving the American policy,"
Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions will not be lifted until UNSCOM certifies
that Baghdad has destroyed all banned weapons. Upset by the
U.S. stance, Iraqi leaders have vowed to lift the crippling
sanctions within this year.
</P>
<P>
In February, tensions reached the brink of military
confrontation when U.S. and British forces were dispatched to the
Gulf to pressure Iraq to comply with the inspections.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan defused the crisis by
brokering an agreement with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to open
eight presidential palaces to inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The situation was further improved in June when Butler gave
Iraq a "blueprint" of what it must do to comply with
U.N. resolutions that must be met for the sanctions to be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Butler and UNSCOM specialists arrived in Baghdad Sunday to
determine the progress made in Iraq's disarmament efforts.
</P>
<P>
After two fruitless rounds of talks Monday, the two sides
seemed to be heading for a crisis once again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
