<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TAZARA Eyes Rwanda, Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania-Zambia Railway (TAZARA)
is looking for funds to extend its rail line from Kasama in
Zambia's Northern Province to its northern port Mpulungu on the
Tanganyika Lake in order to eventually expand its services to
Burundi and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by TAZARA Managing Director, Kingston
Mkandawire, during the just-ended three-day Agriculture and
Commercial Show in Lusaka, Zambia Daily Mail reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The extention of the TAZARA line will boost business among the
three countries-- Zambia, Burundi and Rwanda, said Mkandawire.
</P>
<P>
The call for the development of the stretch Kasama-Mpulungu,
on which cargo is currently carried by trucks, follows a recent
request from Burundian Commerce Minister Gregoire Banyiyezako for
co-financing the construction of the rail line with Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Burundi imports and exports 75 percent of its goods through
Mpulungu Port.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government, however, is yet to respond to the
call, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The rail line has for a long time been transporting goods like
maize, fertiliser, cement and sugar from Zambia to these
countries using trucks via Kasaka, a route which takes a lot of
time.
</P>
<P>
Mkandawire said that cargo transport to Burundi and Rwanda by
railway will be cheap and safe as the
rail company has an ambitious plan aiming at better services.
</P>
<P>
He added that TAZARA has in the past lost customers who
prefered Beira port of Mozambique and Durban in South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
