<HEADLINE> Jilin Province Lavishes Investment in Technical Upgrading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Jilin Province, an old
industrial base in northeast China, has earmarked eight billion
yuan for technical upgrading projects this year, a rise of 39
percent over last year's investment for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Most of the investment will go into 30 major industrial
projects now undergoing structural adjustments, and 64 key state
projects, said a local official.
</P>
<P>
These projects will generate an extra 56.8 billion yuan in
earnings from sales, and 9.8 billion yuan in pre-tax profits
annually, when their respective technical upgrading is completed.
</P>
<P>
Now, Jilin is home to 1,930 state-owned enterprises, including
469 large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The province's state-owned enterprises suffered 2.1 billion
yuan in economic losses in the first five months of this year,
according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Deputy governor Li Jieche said his province will pool more
funds to help technical upgrading of the province's enterprises.
</P>
<P>
He added that private businessmen and overseas investors are
all welcome to invest in the upgrading projects in an effort to
turn money-losing state-owned enterprises into profitable ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
