<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait-Funded Irrigation Project Making Progress in Ningxia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A Kuwait-funded irrigation
project in northwest China's Ningxia, home of 1.78 million Chinese
moslems, has been progressing smoothly with first-phase
sub-project to start trial operation next month, according to
local officials.
</P>
<P>
The whole project, China's biggest aid-the-poor water
conservation undertaking, is expected to absorb 3.34 billion yuan
(about 400 million U.S. dollars) of investment and open up 130,000
hectares of irrigated land within six years.
</P>
<P>
The aid-the-poor project is expected to help 200,000 farmers
rise above the country's poverty line and to resettle another
800,000 farmers from poor mountainous counties in southern Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
An official with the regional government said the first-phase
construction of the huge project has received 140 million
U.S. dollars of government loans from Kuwait and is expected to
receive 700 million yuan (about 84 million U.S. dollars) from the
central government as well as 905 million yuan (about 109 million
U.S. dollars) from the local government.
</P>
<P>
He said it is the first Kuwait-funded agricultural project in
China.
</P>
<P>
China has been attaching great attention to the aid-the-poor
project and its impoverished population has been reduced from 250
million in 1978 to 50 million in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Artificially-propagated Giraffe Sets New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- China's first
artificially-propagated female giraffe Andan, now 20 years old,
gave birth to her seventh baby on Monday at the Taiyuan Zoo in
north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Andan thus broke the record for producing baby giraffes in
the zoos in China.
</P>
<P>
The newborn female giraffe is 1.6 meters tall and healthy
under the care of the mother giraffe and zoo workers.
</P>
<P>
The father of the newborn is a six-year-old giraffe who has
been separated from the mother and the baby as a safety precaution.
</P>
<P>
Andan was born in the Beijing Zoo in 1978 and was sent to the
Taiyuan Zoo in 1981. Since 1983, Andan has given birth to two male
giraffes and five females.
</P>
<P>
The average life expectancy of a giraffe is 25 years, according
to experts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Falling in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed lower for the
second straight day in Tokyo Tuesday, depressed by the continued
falling in major overseas stock markets.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 141.50 points, or 0.88
percent, from Monday's close to end at 16,023.58.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, also fell 10.63 points or 0.85 percent to
1,234.61.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 350 million
shares from Monday's 298.99 million shares Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Mining and Metals, which debuted on the exchange Tuesday,
was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Banking shares underwent another round of fall as Japan's still
gropes for a way out of its bad loan mess.
</P>
<P>
Many market participants expect the unwinding of cross-held bank
shares among Japanese corporations to end in the near future, but
traders said that from a technical viewpoint, there is still potential
for further slides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the overnight drop of the Dow Jones Industrial Average
in New York to 8,786.74, its lowest level since late June, was bad
news for Japan's export-heavy blue chips.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,335 issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 668 to 403, with 193 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
