<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG to Have Its First Stock Exchange: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Papua New Guinea (PNG)
Prime Minister Bill Skate Tuesday announced the formation of his
country's first stock exchange and plans to wipe out his country's
budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
In an address to Australia's National Press Club, Skate said
PNG's first stock exchange would be set up, but did not say when
it would be operational.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to bring in a stock exchange in Papua New
Guinea," said the prime minister, who arrived in Australia Sunday
for an official visit.
</P>
<P>
"We're going to put in professional people, it's going to be so
transparent and that is going to give the right signal to the
investors throughout the world."
</P>
<P>
Skate also said he was confident of eradicating the country's
deficit of 400 million Kina (about 168 million U.S. dollars) and
would soon be delivering on long promised plans to reform the
country's financial system.
</P>
<P>
The PNG economy is in crisis, with a collapse in prices for one
of its major exports, timber, plunging the country into debt and
devastating the currency, the Kina.
</P>
<P>
Skate said he planned to wipe out the country's deficit through
a combination of privatizing the state-owned mineral resources
company Orogen and other yet to be disclosed measures.
</P>
<P>
The visiting prime minister's talks with the Australian
government included how Australia could further assist PNG in
dealing with the aftermath of PNG's tsunami disaster, which
devastated a 30-km stretch of the country's remote northwest
coastline and killed more than 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 4.2 million people, PNG, which won
independence from Australia in 1975, is Australia's largest aid
recipient. Australia's annual aid to PNG totals 180 million U.S.
dollars, about 40 percent of the nation's overseas aid budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
