<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Jobs, Higher Pay for Graduates in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The number of university and
college graduates obtaining employment in New Zealand has fallen
for the first time since 1992, though those finding jobs are
earning more, according to a recruitment survey here.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which was published Tuesday in The Evening Post, a
Wellington-based newspaper, said the Asian financial crisis could
be blamed for some firms cancelling or curbing their graduate
recruitment programs.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed a 15.2 percent fall in graduates getting jobs
in the year ending June 1998, compared to the previous year.
</P>
<P>
"These results are significant, given that this is the first
time since the survey began in 1992 that we have seen a decrease,"
the paper quoted survey team leader Kevin McBride as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, salaries rose between 2.7 percent to 8
percent. Median-base salaries for graduates in their first year
working climbed to 32,000 N.Z. dollars (16,300 U.S. dollars) from
30.500 N.Z. dollars (15,600 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
