<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Doubled in Four Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian police has increased
its personnel from 6,000 nationwide in 1994 by over 100 percent
under a recently launched reform program.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Beenwell Chimfwembe said in an interview here
Monday that there are currently about 13,000 policemen and that
the Zambian government is targeting to recruit up to 27,000 by
the year 2000, the government-owned Zambia Daily Mail reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Chimfwembe did not say whether there are external donors
financing the reforms, but he said that the exercise was
initiated by the Zambian government and that the resources from
donor countries are being channeled to the areas it thinks
worthwhile, including the police service.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government has promised to release money for the
acquisition of communication equipment, the rehabilitation of
police stations and accommodation in police camps, said the
police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Chimfwembe noted that the whole exercise is, however,
dependent on how quickly the funds are made available.
</P>
<P>
He added that since Lusaka is experiencing an upswing in
crime, it will be given priority in the acquisition of utility
equipment.
</P>
<P>
In the past months, Lusaka has been experiencing a series of
armed robberies and brutal manslaughters which forced the police
to intensify their fight against the ever rising crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
