<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Proposes New Ideas at Talks: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel proposed several "new
ideas" on its West Bank troop withdrawal at the talks held with
Palestinian negotiators Monday night, Israel Radio reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's legal advisor Yitzhak
Molcho met for several hours secretly with chief Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat at a undisclosed location in Jerusalem, but
neither side would say whether enough progress was made to keep
the talks going.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Israeli sources as saying that the Israel put
forward several "new ideas" at the meeting and was waiting for
response from the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
But the report did not disclose what the new ideas are. The
Palestinian side had warned before the Monday talks that if Israel
did not come up with new ideas, the round of talks would be the
last.
</P>
<P>
Erekat went directly to Gaza after the meeting to brief Yasser
Arafat, President of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), on
the talks.
</P>
<P>
The chief Palestinian negotiator said "nothing special" was
produced at the Monday talks.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Erekat demanded that Israel present its
withdrawal map to explain where was the proposed 3 percent area,
which Israel wants to turn into nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and other top palestinian officials would review the
session's outcome and then decide what steps to take next, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said it was still too earlier to say whether the
PNA would halt the talks, which were resumed on July 19 with an
aim to break the 16 month long deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The sticking point is that Israel has rejected the U.S. plan
calling for a 13.1 percent withdrawal, which the PNA has already
endorsed.
</P>
<P>
In the earlier rounds of talks, Israel proposed that 3 percent
of the proposed withdrawal be turned into nature reserves in which
both sides should refrain from building. The PNA has so far
refused to accept the demand, citing it had already made
compromise by accepting the trimmed U.S. pullback plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
