<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least seven people were killed, 15 seriously
injured and 90 others feared trapped under the debris when a
seven-storey building collapsed Monday night in a northwest
suburb of Mumbai, India's commercial capital.
</P>
<P>
The "Govind Apartments", which crumbled to the ground around
2005 local time yesterday, housed shops on the ground floor,
residential apartments on the first, second and third floors and a
 hotel on the upper three, the Statesman newspaper reported
Tuesday, quoting fire brigade sources. (BC-India-Collapses)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Sri Lanka will host the Asian Congress of
Architects in Colombo from November 10 to 15 this year, in which
around 500 international delegates from 15 Asian countries are
expected to participate.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Congress of Architects (ACA) is the meeting of the
Architects Regional Council of Asia (ARCA) that takes place once
in two years in a member country since 1980. (BC-Sri Lanka-ACA
Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- Bulgaria Monday denied accusations that it was engaged
in armament trade with terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
In response to a New York Times report, the Bulgarian Ministry
of Trade and Tourism said that the Bulgarian government has never
granted licenses to any Bulgarian companies for exporting weapons
to terrorist organizations. (BC-Bulgaria-Arms Sales)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Armed clashes between Serb police and ethnic
Albanians have flared up again in southwest Kosovo and casualties
have been reported on both sides.
</P>
<P>
In a Monday-Tuesday fight against a charge of ethnic Albanian
militants, the Serb police successfully defended their position
and killed a dozen militants, the information center in Pristina
said. (BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Clashes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Danilo Turk, the current president of the
Security Council of the United Nations, said on Monday that the
disarmament talks between the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM) and Iraq have broken down.
</P>
<P>
Turk said Richard Butler, Executive Chairman of UNSCOM in
charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, would
come back to the Headquarters of the United Nations in New York on
Wednesday to brief the Council on his trip to
Iraq.(BC-UN-Iraq-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian government has taken serious
measures to investigate the acts of violence during the May
riots, local press Tuesday quoted Chairman of the Joint
Fact-finding Team Marzuki Darusman as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The formation of the Joint Fact-finding Team is proof of the
government's seriousness in uncovering the acts of violence,
including rapes of ethnic Chinese women", Marzuki told a group of
Taiwanese women human rights activists here Monday.
(BC-Indonesia-May Riot-Investigation) 
