<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.S. Firm to Jointly Utilize Yak Blood Component </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Qinghai Province in northwest
China has reached an agreement with a U.S. biology-technology
corporation to jointly utilize the blood of yaks, which contains
large amounts of a commercial substance known as SOD (super
dioxide dismutase).
</P>
<P>
Yaks are one of the province's most abundant animals, living at
elevations of more than 3,000 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Yu Mantang, a Chinese researcher, found that yak blood contains
large amounts of SOD while conducting gene research on the blood
of the animal. Yu also discovered that the SOD content of the yak
blood is three times that of domestic animals in inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Yaks living in China's Qinghai and Sichuan provinces as well as
the Tibet Autonomous Region are estimated at more than 14 million,
accounting for 85 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
SOD has wide applications in pharmaceuticals, food, nutrition
and cosmetics. Agreements have been reached with the KuiXave
Biolink Inc, a U.S.-based corporation, to introduce advanced
equipment for manufacturing SOD products.
</P>
<P>
Preparations have been under way for the project, which is
expected to boost poverty-relief efforts in the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regeneration Technique Helps Severed Foot Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Regenration technique has helped
a Chinese patient's severed left foot grow by five centimeters in
about three months.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Chinese doctors have used this
technique on a severed foot.
</P>
<P>
The 42-year-old patient in Dalian City, northeast China, had
his left foot cut off by a steel wire last December, and the
remaining portion of the foot was only eight centimeters long,
making it impossible to walk.
</P>
<P>
Doctors from the No. 5 People's Hospital in Dalian and their
counterparts from Japan's Tokyo University used the regeneration
technique which included installing bone-lengthening equipment on
the severed foot to help the bone grow.
</P>
<P>
According to the doctors, the foot grew by one millimeter daily
during the three-month procedure.
</P>
<P>
They said they now have taken the bone-lengthening equipment
off the patient, as the injured foot has basically resumed its
function.
</P>
<P>
The doctors predict the patient will be able to walk normally in
another three months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 07:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crimes in Israel Continue to Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Israel's serious crimes hit a
record high of 4,492 in the first half of this year, continuing an
upward trend in the past years, the Haaretz daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Serious crime is defined to include murder, attempted murder,
rape, indecent assault, arson, robbery, blackmail and bribery.
</P>
<P>
Just two years ago, in the first half of 1996, there were 3,604
cases categorized as serious crimes, according to police
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Police records showed 13,605 cases of personal attacks,
including rape, in the first half of 1998, an increase of 10
percent from 12,380 in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, offenses of disturbing public order climbed 4.6
percent from the same period of 1997, and the number of recorded
drug offenses among the youth rose to 503 from 457. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Hong Kong People Choose to Work on Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Emily commutes to work from
Hong Kong to Guangzhou by direct bus every Monday.
</P>
<P>
She left her job in Hong Kong because there she was only an
ordinary staff worker, but now she is a mid-level executive at a
Sino-foreign joint venture in the capital of south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The number of Hong Kong people looking for jobs in neighboring
Guangdong is on the rise. For example, the Hong Kong Branch of the
Guangzhou-based South China Human Resources Market opened in March
and has so far received 200 applications and 600 inquiries.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong residents are mostly welcomed by local
enterprises. "Our company wants to lure property experts from Hong
Kong, since Hong Kong has a mature property market," said
Mr. Zhao, the head of a real estate company in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
According to Director Pan of the Guangzhou Municipal Personnel
Bureau, the human resources of Guangdong and Hong Kong are
complementary. The rich resource of experienced personnel in
finance, trade, enterprise management and real estate are most
welcomed by Guangdong Province, which has one of the most dynamic
economies in China.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, more and more electrical and computer
technicians are coming from Guangdong to work in Hong Kong to fill
the shortage there, thanks to intensified personnel exchanges
between the two places.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
