<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Industrialists Apply for Prices Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of Zimbabwe
Industries has applied to the government for price increases of
maize meal, flour, cooking oils and bread.
</P>
<P>
Acting Chief Executive of the confedeation, Farai Zizhou told
a news conference here Monday that manufacturers expected the
government to make a decision on the matter "in the very near
future", the Zimbabwe News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Although there is no legislation preventing price increases
of edible oils, wheat, flour and bread, manufacturers have not
unilaterally increased prices of their products following a
government/business understanding reached early in the year,"
Zizhou said.
</P>
<P>
He said that significant adjustments were necessary to prevent
the collapse of a number of companies as manufacturers had been
facing massive cost increases for raw materials, electricity,
wages, transport, packaging and services.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturers have proposed to increase the price of maize
meal by 14.5 percent, flour by 20.05 percent, cooking oils by
12.5 percent and bread by 21.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zizhou said the proposed increases are a result of price hikes
of raw materials which rose by between 8.3 percent and 57.14
percent with packaging costs up to 20 percent, financing costs hiking
to 35 percent, post and telecommunications charges up to 50
percent, and wage increases of between 30 and 34 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
