<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese-Made Parts For Sino-French Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese-made components used in
producing two types of "Citroen-Fukang" cars by a Sino-French
automobile joint venture in Central China account for more than 80
percent of the cars' parts, up from 60 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Some 82.17 percent of the parts used to build the 1.4-liter
series "Citroen-Fukang" are made in China, and 80.78 percent
domestic parts are used in "Citroen-Fukang" cars with
electronic-direct-injection motors.
</P>
<P>
The Dongfeng-Citroen Automobile Company was jointly built by
France's Citroen Automobile company in Wuhan, capital of Hubei
Province, at a cost of nearly 10.4 billion yuan for the first
phase of construction, one of the country's largest Sino-foreign
joint venture of its kind.
</P>
<P>
This joint venture began operations in 1996 and is expected
ultimately to turn out 300,000 "Citroen-Fukang" cars a year. It
can now produce a dozen varieties of 1.4-liter and 1.6-liter
"Citroen-Fukangs."
</P>
<P>
And Chinese-made components now account for 67.46 percent of
the parts used in producing the 1.6-liter "Citroen-Fukang."
</P>
<P>
As many as 167 different auto-parts makers in China provide
components for the joint venture.
</P>
<P>
The company has now invested 700 million yuan to install
quality-control facilities for products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
