<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joined Twins Born in Central China's Hunan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- A pair of joined female twins
have been born in Liuyang City in central China's Hunan Province,
a rarely seen event in China in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The twins, joined together from the chest to the abdomen, were
born on August 1 and weighed 4.4 kilograms. One of the girls
was also born with a cleft palate.
</P>
<P>
The baby girls were transferred from No.5 Liuyang Hospital to
the Hunan Children's Hospital in Changsha for better treatment.
</P>
<P>
The twins often touch each other with their four hands and
blink their eyes simultaneously when facing the camera as someone
takes their picture.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Jianxin, father of the twins, said his wife had been in
good conditions while pregnant and he never expected to have
joined twins.
</P>
<P>
The twins' mother had ultrasonic testing in the fifth month of
pregnancy, and the fetus was discovered to have two heads and two
hearts.
</P>
<P>
Doctors thought the fetus was twins, and the mother had no
further testing after that.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Zhou Xiaoyu at the children's hospital said the survival
rate for joined twins is very low, and their survival depends on
early separation.
</P>
<P>
The doctor emphasised that smooth separation depends on the
overall condition of the twins.
</P>
<P>
Plans for the separation operation are expected to be made
after a complete physical examination of the joined girls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Currency Crashes Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Value of the Zimbabwean Dollar
has dropped again under heavy speculative pressure from
importers.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate fell to the level of 25 Zimbabwean Dollars
to one U.S. Dollar Monday before the Reserve Bank intervened late
in the day, freezing the rate at 23 Zimbabwean Dollars to the
U.S. Dollar, the daily Herald newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some commercial banks were Monday buying U.S. Dollars for 21
Zimbabwean Dollars and selling them for 25 Zimbabwean Dollars,
the huge margin showing the volatility and uncertainty of
trading.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe, said in a
statement Monday that it had become necessary to raise the
rediscount rate to bring about stability to the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The rediscount rate, the rate at which other banks borrow from
the Reserve Bank went up from 31.5 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Domestic price inflation, the statement said, had
progressively increased from 20.1 percent in December last year
to about 30 percent by June this year. This had caused real
rates to be eroded.
</P>
<P>
To hike the rediscount rate by 3.5 percent will in turn
force the commercial banks to increase their minimum lending
rates. This will make borrowing from banks by both businesses and
individuals more expensive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
