<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Building Collapses in Mumbai, Killing Seven </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- At least seven people were
killed, 15 seriously injured and 90 others feared trapped under
the debris when a seven-storey building collapsed Monday night in
a northwest suburb of Mumbai, India's commercial capital.
</P>
<P>
The "Govind Apartments", which crumbled to the ground around
2005 local time yesterday, housed shops on the ground floor,
residential apartments on the first, second and third floors and a
hotel on the upper three, the Statesman newspaper reported
Tuesday, quoting fire brigade sources.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers pulled 13 people from the rubble and admitted them to
three city hospitals while two others were discharged after first
aid, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Residents said there was some unauthorized construction on the
top floor and they had complained to the municipality that the
15-year-old building had been tilting to one side for some months.
</P>
<P>
The police said, however, the civic authorities had served an
eviction notice to the residents, but they had stayed on
disregarding safety.
</P>
<P>
Another daily, the National Herald, said today that such
incidents have been a regular feature in the commercial capital of
the country during the last few years.
</P>
<P>
On the average, according to the daily, three to four buildings
collapse every year in Mumbai, killing scores of people.
</P>
<P>
Municipal authorities have become rather strict in granting
permission to build high-rise buildings in the megalopolis due to
such unfortunate incidents, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
