<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Situation Improving Gradually in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The overall flood situation in
Bangladesh is gradually improving with water in the major rivers
receding, according to the Flood Information Center (FIC) here.
</P>
<P>
But the situation might deteriorate again in northern and
northwestern areas of the Ganges and Brahmaputra basins and upper
parts of Meghna basin due to heavy downpour, the FIC warned
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Flood situation in the districts along both the Padma and
Brahmaputra-Jamuna rivers are likely to improve, but in the
central parts of the country and around Dhaka city, it might
remain unchanged, the FIC added.
</P>
<P>
Till now, 17.4 million people in the 37 districts out of the
total of 64 have been affected by flood, which has also damaged
and washed away 5,100 kilometers of roads, 2,396 kilometers of
embankment with 2,215 bridges and culverts and about 200,000
hectares of crop land, and perished 5,522 cattle, according to a
preliminary estimate.
</P>
<P>
To help the flood victims, the government has so far opened 429
camps where about 12,480 people took shelter, and the government
departments concerned have distributed 13.2 million taka (about
280,850 U.S. dollars), about 28,800 tons of grain and other needed
relief materials among the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Diarrhea, dysentery and other water-born diseases have already
broken out in some flood-hit areas, with over 41,000 people having
fallen victims, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
To contain the spread of the diseases, the government
departments concerned have already sent 3,773 medical teams with
1,666 doctors to the areas in 37 districts till Monday, and at the
same time 75 temporary medical centers have also been opened
across the country to provide treatment to the flood victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
