<HEADLINE> China Undecided on Importing Disney's "Mulan" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Reliable sources told Xinhua
today that China has not yet decided whether to import Walt
Disney's cartoon feature film "Mulan."
</P>
<P>
The sources said that although the film has already been
translated into Chinese, the Chinese government needs time to
discuss whether to import the movie, which is based on a Chinese
folk story.
</P>
<P>
China imports a limited number of foreign films annually,
accounting for only 10 to 15 percent of the films distributed in
the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
The artistic taste and story line of a foreign movie, and
the Chinese government's policies are both elements affecting the
decision-making process, they said.
</P>
<P>
An official from the China Film Corporation said that whether
or not to import "Mulan" will be a complicated issue.
</P>
<P>
The only imported film from Walt Disney has been Mickey Mouse
movies, but that was many years ago.
</P>
<P>
"Mulan" has been translated into six languages and has
attracted worldwide attention. Fans have opened more than 30 sites
about the movie on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Hua Mulan was an ancient Chinese heroine who served in
the army in place of her old and sickly father. Nobody guessed she
was a female until the war ended, because she well disguised
herself as a man.
</P>
<P>
Some Walt Disney producers have said that Mulan represents the
trend of women's liberation, and equality between men and women,
according to media reports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0210 </DOCNO>
