<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Denies Arms Sales to Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria Monday denied accusations
that it was engaged in armament trade with terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
In response to a New York Times report, the Bulgarian Ministry
of Trade and Tourism said that the Bulgarian government has never
granted licenses to any Bulgarian companies for exporting weapons
to terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria strictly observes all restrictions imposed by the
United Nations Security Council, including the embargo on arms
sales to a list of countries "with poor human rights records or
aggressive designs on their neighbors," the Bulgarian Telegraph
Agency (BTA) quoted the ministry as saying.
</P>
<P>
In any case where Bulgarian-made weapons are resold to
terrorist organizations, the Bulgarian government shall not be
held responsible, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
In Bulgaria, the Commission for Controlling and Licensing
Foreign Trade in Arms and Dual-purpose Technologies, under the
Ministry of Trade and Tourism, is the only organization which has
the right to issue export licenses to Bulgarian companies.
</P>
<P>
The BTA said the New York Times alleged that Bulgaria "has
turned into an armament market for rebels and terrorists of all
sorts of political, ethnic and religious organizations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
