<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Exports to India To Increase Four-fold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's exports to India will
increase four-fold once the Indian government removes tariff
barriers on 2000 products in October this year, according to trade
ministry sources here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the South Asian Summit recently, Indian leader announced
that India would remove these tariff barriers, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They quoted Trade Minister Kingsley Wickremaratne as saying
that the product range which will find lucrative markets in India
include spices, fibre and fibre based products, rubber and rubber
based products, graphite, gems and jewelry among a host of others.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka at present has 380 commodities available for export
to India, of which 106 items have been requested by Sri Lanka for
the removal of tariff barriers by India.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that a further boon to the promotion of Sri
Lankan exports to India was the reduction in the criteria in
relation to the Rules of Origin whereby value addition of products
in the South Asian region needed to be only 30 percent for exports
within the region while earlier it was 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
This will not only pave the way for additional exports from Sri
Lanka to India but also for joint ventures and alliances in
industry and commerce.
</P>
<P>
At present Sri Lanka exports 47 million U.S. dollars worth of
commodities to India and imports 187.5 million dollars worth of
commodities from India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands to Provide Fund for River Dredging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will get 15 million U.S.
dollars from the Netherlands government for dredging of Gorai
river, it was learned from the Netherlands Embassy here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An agreement in this regard was signed here Monday between
Bangladesh and the Dutch dredging company, Boskalis.
</P>
<P>
The work on the 30 million dollar-project is expected to begin
next month, and the Bangladeshi government will contribute the
remaining 15 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
After the Ganges Water Treaty signed in 1996 between Bangladesh
and India, the possibility of opening the mouth of the Gorai river
by capital dredging has been explored.
</P>
<P>
The project, when it is implemented, will allow fresh water to
flow into the Southwest region of Bangladesh, and the fresh water
flow will reverse the salinity in the region, retard the process
of "top dying" of Sundari trees in the southwest Bangladesh's
Sundarbans mangrove, the largest on in the world, which is being
seriously threatened by "top-Dying Disease".
</P>
<P>
Besides, the project will also have major positive impact on
agriculture, on drinking water supply and on the industries of the
country's southwestern region of Khulna. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
