<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Finds Way to Build Faster Computer Chips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 3 (Xinhua) -- International Business
Machines Corp. said Monday it has found a way of making
microprocessor chips that can boost their performance by 35
percent, according to reports from the company.
</P>
<P>
The computer giant said in a statement that its "silicon-on-
insulator" (SOI) technology is a key advance that will allow it to
make chips with a special insulation layer between each transistor
and the chips' silicon base, reducing electrical interference that
saps energy and performance.
</P>
<P>
SOI, which comes just 11 months after IBM's previous microchip
breakthrough -- the copper chip -- can require as little as a
third of the power used by current chips, thus extending battery
life for portable devices such as cellular phones and hand-held
computers, IBM said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe SOI, with its high-performance and low-power
characteristics, is a significant breakthrough in chip
technology," said Mike Attardo, general manager of IBM
microelectronics division. "Like our copper chips, SOI will
accelerate the industry's constant drive to create smaller, more
powerful, less expensive electronic goods," he added.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say that, using the new technology, a
computer microprocessor designed to run at 400 megahertz could run
at more than 500 MHz.
</P>
<P>
While other companies also have been working on SOI technology,
IBM said it would be the first to introduce it commercially.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Piped Gas Replaces Straw for Cooking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese farmers are saying
farewell to the traditional use of straw as cooking fuel since
newly developed piped gas, made from straw, is entering into rural
households.
</P>
<P>
Using straw as firewood has a long history in China. But,
compared with natural gas popular in the cities, it is inefficient
and causes pollution to the environment.
</P>
<P>
With the new method invented by the Energy Research Institute
of the Shandong Provincial Academy of Sciences, straw is ground up
before being gasified and piped into households.
</P>
<P>
On the average, one kilogram of straw can produce two cubic
meters of gas, thus more than double the calories of straw
burning, according to Sun Li, a research fellow at the institute.
</P>
<P>
Teng Shaohua, a farmer in Shandong Province, said cooking is
much more convenient now that her village has built a gas station
using straw as materials. "Just turn it on," she said, showing
the reporter her new gas utensil, "It's no longer sooty and smoky."
</P>
<P>
A straw gas station usually costs 300,000 yuan (36,100 U.S.
dollars), and each family only pays 15 to 18 yuan per month for
the supply.
</P>
<P>
Each year, China produces 700 million tons of straw, of which
about half is used for fodder and manure, and the rest become
fuel.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Science and Technology has decided to
popularize this technology across the country. To date, this type
of gas has been introduced into over 20,000 households in over 100
villages in Shandong, Hebei, Heilongjiang, Anhui, Henan and
Shaanxi provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakia's Trade Deficit Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia's trade deficit went up
18 percent or 180 million U.S. dollars in the first half of this
year, amounting to 1.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Slovak Statistics Bureau says Slovakia imported 6.8 billion
dollar worth of goods in the first six months of this year,
while its exports reached only 5.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia's economic experts said the deficit was the highest
for the same period in three years.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia has seen its trade deficit climb since 1995 when it
registered a deficit of 178 million dollars. The deficit amounted
to 2.19 billion dollars in 1996, and 2.18 billion dollars in
1997. 
