<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earmarked Loans to be used to Help Industry in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will use a
122.9-million-U.S.-dollars loan obtained from the Asian
Development Bank and the World Bank for the first phase of its
industrial restructuring program, according to Industry Minister
Somsak Thepsuthin.
</P>
<P>
The funds were earmarked for the manufacturing sector,
particularly those geared toward exports, Somsak was quoted
Tuesday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the money will be used to upgrade production processes,
raise productivity and create more employment.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bank of Thailand, the country's manufacturing
index contracted by 17.4 percent in may. Most industries except
textiles slipped due to the liquidity squeeze and declining
demand.
</P>
<P>
A new national industrial restructuring master plan has
identified 13 strategic sectors that need to be overhauled.
</P>
</TEXT>
