<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Tourist Arrivals Down in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of foreign tourist
arrivals in the Czech Republic continued to decline, down 2.3
percent in the first half of this year from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The country attracted 48.2 million foreign visitors in the
first six months, the smallest number for the same period in
recent years, according to the Czech Statistical Office.
</P>
<P>
The catering sector was the first to fall victim to the
decrease, with its retail sales plunging 13 percent and the
occupancy rate of hotels plummeting considerably.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic enjoyed increases for five consecutive years
in foreign tourist arrivals and tourism-related revenues since
1992. In 1996, foreign tourist arrivals in the country hit 100
million while tourism-related revenues amounted to 4 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tourism, one of the Czech Republic's pillar industries, began
to suffer from unstable political situation, depressed economy and
deteriorated tourism services in 1997. The country's revenues
from tourism dropped by more than 10 percent in that year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
