<HEADLINE> U.N. Disarmament Talks with Baghdad Breaks Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Danilo Turk, the current
president of the Security Council of the United Nations, said on
Monday that the disarmament talks between the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) and Iraq have broken down.
</P>
<P>
Turk said Richard Butler, Executive Chairman of UNSCOM in
charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, would
come back to the Headquarters of the United Nations in New York on
Wednesday to brief the Council on his trip to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"This is a difficult time. It is disturbing. We will have to
see what Butler brings," Turk said.
</P>
<P>
Butler, who went to Baghdad days ago, brought with him a "road
map" for Iraq to follow in its disarmament, and it was unclear
what has caused the breakdown of the talks, Turk added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under U.N. sanctions since its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990. The U.N. says that sanctions will not be lifted until
Iraq has destroyed all its prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and UNSCOM has been at odds recently. Iraq reiterates
that It has complied with relevant U.N. resolutions and destroyed
all its weapons of Mass destruction. But UNSCOM holds that Iraq
still has much progress to make in the areas of ballistic
missiles, chemical and biological weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
