<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't to Help Firms Settle Foreign Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
ready to help private companies service 60 percent of their
foreign debts which will mature in one to two years, an official
said.
</P>
<P>
The government's Debt Restructuring Agency (INDRA) wants to
help reschedule the repayment of corporate debts that will mature
this year and spread them over eight years, INDRA Chairman Sumitro
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,000 companies have reported their corporate debts to the
central bank, Bank Indonesia, Antara News Agency Tuesday quoted
Sumitro as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia had a total of 138 billion U.S. dollars foreign debts
by the end of April, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country's corporate and interbank debts have
reached 74.3 billion U.S. dollars, consisting of 60.3 billion
dollars possessed by private companies and 13.6 incurred by banks.
</P>
<P>
The corporate debt which will mature this year amounts to 34
billion U.S. dollars, consisting of 27 billion dollars incurred by
private companies and 7 billion dollars possessed by banks.
</P>
<P>
Sumitro said only companies which have agreed with foreign
creditors to restructure the repayment of their debts over eight
years could use the services of INDRA.
</P>
<P>
INDRA is voluntary in nature, meaning it does not require all
companies with foreign debts to joint it. he said, adding they are
free to settle their corporate debts on their own.
</P>
<P>
"They could settle (their foreign debts) using the bankruptcy
law or through direct negotiations with foreign creditors," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts held that the private debt was one the major
reasons for the prolonged economic crisis in Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Doubles Foreign Investment in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Italy almost doubled its foreign
direct investment in 1997, according to a survey released by
Eurostat, Monday.
</P>
<P>
Investment by Italian firms and agencies in foreign countries
rose by 84 percent from just over 5 billion Ecus (5.4 billion
U.S. dollars) to 9.4 billion Ecus (10 billion dollars) compared
with the previous year, Eurostat said.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the new investment, 5.66 billion Ecus (6.2 billion
dollars), went to other EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Direct inward investment into Italy rose by just 17 percent, on
the other hand, from 2.78 billion Ecus (3 billion dollars) to 3.26
billion Ecus (3.6 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The balance between Italy's inward and outward capital flows
rose threefold, from 2.3 billion Ecus (2.5 billion dollars) to 6.1
Ecus (6.6 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Germany had the biggest investment deficit, 29.4 billion Ecus
(32 billion dollars), as outward flows rose by 26 percent, while
inward investment in Germany tumbled by 92 percent.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by the United Kingdom's deficit of 19.9
billion Ecus (21.7 billion dollars), the Netherlands' 10.4 billion
Ecus (11 billion dollars) and France's 7.9 billion Ecus (8.6
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the 15 EU members, only Austria, Portugal and
Belgium/Luxembourg (taken together) had an investment surplus.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat said increasing globalization of the world economy was
leading more and more firms to relocate in cheaper
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
