<HEADLINE> Malta's Premier Announces Early Elections on September 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Maltese Prime Minister Alfred Sant
announced on Monday that a general election would be held on
September 5, three years ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference held in Malta's capital
Valletta, Sant said he made the decision after discussions with
President Ugo Mifsud Bonnici.
</P>
<P>
Elections were not due until 2001, but Sant told the president
that he had to announce early elections because of the unstable
situation within his Labor party.
</P>
<P>
With a one-vote majority in parliament, the ruling Labor party
was sworn in on October 26, 1996. But the party has been divided
on many issues such as government reforms, economic and foreign
policies.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe the decision is based on the crisis
within the ruling party, rather than attacks from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The Labour party won 50.72 percent of the votes in the last
general elections, enabling it to oust the Nationalist Party which
had been in power since 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
