<HEADLINE> Philippines to Import More Sugar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has approved the importation of 154,453 metric tons of raw
sugar and authorized the Sugar Regulatory Authority (SRA) to
facilitate the import of sugar by the private sector to avert a
possible shortage.
</P>
<P>
Estrada directed in a memorandum Monday night SRA Administrator
Nicolas Alonzo to initiate the importation of the raw sugar
through the National Sugar Planters Federation, The Business Daily
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Millers and farmers have been asking government to import up to
200,000 tons of sugar in the current crop year ending August 31 to
meet the rising consumption by the local beverage industry.
</P>
<P>
Government has so far approved the initial importation of
45,547 tons which is the minimum access volume allowed under World
Trade Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Estrada assured the public that there was enough
supply of sugar following reports that the country would be left
with only about 113,000 tons of sugar from carryover stocks by the
end of August.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted SRA source as saying that the country will
source the 154,453 tons raw sugar from Australia and Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
