<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Becomes Fourth Largest Contributor to EU Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Italy was the fourth largest
contributor to the 1997 European Union budget following Germany,
France and Britain, the EU budget commission said.
</P>
<P>
Italy accounted for more than 11 percent of the total EU
budget, with a contribution of 8.66 billions Ecus (9.4 billion
U.S. dollars) to the total budget of 76.16 billion Ecus (83
billion dollars), the Italian news agency ANSA quoted a
commission report as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The largest slice of the EU budget, or 45 percent, came from a
quota of the revenue drawn by the member states from value added
tax, while 35 percent came from a percentage of each country's
gross national product (GNP).
</P>
<P>
The remaining 20 percent was from agricultural duties and other
tariffs imposed on non-EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures are "sensitive" in view of a fund debate
linked to the planned EU enlargement to include some Central and
Eastern European nations in the next decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
