<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin America in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- The gross domestic product (GDP) in
Colombia grew by 5.69 percent in the first three months of 1998,
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Statistics National Administration Department attributed
the rise to the 12.24 percent increase in the manufacturing
industry.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Real estate agents have decided to establish a
Southern Common Market (MERCOSUR) Real Estate Confederation and
approve a common registry for operations in the regions.
</P>
<P>
These initiatives will enable real estate brokers of MERCOSUR
countries, and Chile and Bolivia, to extend their businesses to
the regional market with the population of 230 million people.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The index of consumption prices in Chile was up 0.4
percent in July and 2.3 percent in the first seven months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The National Statistics Institute said food price rose by 0.5
percent, housing by 0.2 percent and transportation and
communications by 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan stock market jumped by 154 percent
in July to 4.03 billion dollars, compared with July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The market totalled 1,684 billion dollars in the first seven
months, a 306 percent rise over the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica received more than 52,000 foreign
visitors in June, a 19 percent increase over the same period in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The number of American tourists who traveled to this country
grew by 27.5 percent, while tourists from Britain and Spain were
up 12.5 percent and 34.3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican foreign exchange earned by tourism was up 18.9
percent, from 53.9 million dollars in June 1997 to 64.1 million
dollars in June 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
