<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) has
approved contingency plans for possible use of military force in
the Kosovo crisis, said the United States on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"NATO has now approved a range of contingency plans for the use
of military force," said State Department spokesman James Rubin at
a regular briefing. However, he added that the plans needs to be
further refined. (US-Kosovo-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The talks on weapons inspection between the
U.N. chief arms inspector Richard Butler and Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz broke down Monday.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Butler's refusal to go to the U.N. Security Council
to tell the truth about disarmament issue in Iraq led to the
break-down of the talks.
</P>
<P>
This is the first break-down of talks between Iraq and UNSCOM,
or the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq, which
indicates that their relations are worsening. (Iraq-UN-Talks 2nd
lead Writethru)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government Monday appealed to India and
Pakistan to start immediate peace talks in an effort to resolve
their border clashes which have killed more than 80 people over
the past few days.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Office minister Derek Fatchett said in a
statement issued early Monday, "Recent reports of shootings across
the Line of Control can only add to the already high levels of
tension."  (UK-Talks-India-Pakistan) 
</P>
