<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Campaign Finance Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives approved Monday a bill that would reform campaign
finance laws.
</P>
<P>
The House approved a measure to ban so-called "soft money" --
unregulated donations that go to party committees rather than
political candidates. The bill still faces competition from other
House campaign finance proposals due for votes later this week and
a potential barrier in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The measure, sponsored by Representatives Christopher Shays of
Connecticut and Marty Meehan of Massachusetts, would place tighter
restrictions on "issue advocacy" ads within 60 days of an
election. Those ads theoretically do not target individual
candidates and are therefore not subject to federal disclosure
laws.
</P>
<P>
The bill, approved on a 237-186 vote, survived weeks of debate
and votes on amendments its backers said were designed to strip
away support and splinter the bipartisan coalition in favor of
revamping fund-raising laws.
</P>
<P>
The vote on the bill, which is similar to one that died in the
Senate earlier this year, will be followed this week by votes on
nine remaining campaign finance measures pitted against one
another in a wide-ranging debate that began in May. The leading
vote-getter wins.
</P>
<P>
But Senate Republican leaders have shown little inclination to
even take up the issue when they return from their summer recess
in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smokers in New Zealand Under Intense Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 4 (Xinhua) -- Smokers in New Zealand will
come under intense pressure to stub out smoking as New Zealand
Associate Health Minister Tuariki Delamere has disclosed his plans
"to hit smokers in the pocket through another tax rise".
</P>
<P>
Delamere's open hostility towards smokers came as Smokingfree
Coalition research was released showing smoking had fallen 10
percent since tax rise of 50 cents a packet in May this year.
</P>
<P>
This year's tax rise was the first in seven years, with tax
making up about 70 percent of the price of each packet.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion, a Wellington-based newspaper, today quoted the
New Zealand associate health minister as saying that tougher
measures remained his goal, including a smoking ban in public
buildings and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
Delamere told an Action on Smoking and Health meeting here
yesterday evening that he wanted the tax to rise another 50 cents
a packet in next year's budget, pushing the price close to eight
NZ dollars (more than four U.S. dollars) a packet.
</P>
<P>
"It's my goal to literally destroy (tobacco companies)," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"They know full well that smoking is a killer but they are so
well versed in the art of deception and exploiting peer pressure
to lure teenagers," Delamere said.
</P>
<P>
According to the associate health minister, there are about
4,500 smoking-related deaths a year in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Smokingfree Coalition Director Barbara Langford said at the
meeting that the new research findings showed a price rise was the
right spur for some to quit smoking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
