<HEADLINE> Agreement Reached over N. Irish Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A Protestant brotherhood and
Catholic residents in Northern Irish city of Londonderry reached
an "understanding" over a potential flashpoint parade on Monday,
reports from Belfast said.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough came after a weekend of negotiation between
the pro-British Protestant Apprentice Boys and the Bogside
Residents's Group over Saturday's planned march in Londoderry, the
second largest city in the province.
</P>
<P>
The threat of a confrontation at Saturday's parade had been
casting a shadow over efforts to bring peace to Northern Ireland,
which witnessed a historic peace agreement last April aimed at
ending 30 years of violence.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Apprentice Boys said agreement had been
reached with residents of the mainly Catholic city to permit its
annual march to go ahead on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Its main parade would pass through the city as usual but only
13 representatives would lay a wreath at the city's war memorial,
the scene of ugly clashes in the past, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mo Mowlam, Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary, welcomed the
compromise, saying she hoped it would be an example to other
disputed marches.
</P>
<P>
"It is a victory for common sense and I believe it will be
welcomed eagerly by the people of Derry and indeed throughout the
whole of Northern Ireland," she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It shows what can be achieved when people talk with each other
and respect the other person's point of view," she added.
</P>
<P>
As many as 20,000 people take part in the march every year,
held to commemorate the lifting in 1689 of the Siege of Derry, the
longest military siege in British history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
