<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Indexes to Add Hong Kong "Red Chips" and Drop Portugal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) Monday announced two changes to the components
of the IFC Investable (IFCI) index, to add Hong Kong "red chips"
and drop Portuguese equities.
</P>
<P>
The IFCI index measures returns on stocks that are available to
foreign investors, and the IFC Global (IFCG) index, is designed as
the broadest indicator of market movements, showing the
performance of the most active stocks in their respective stock
markets even if they are unavailable to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, IFC will Hong Kong "red chips" to its
Investable and Global Index series for China on November 2, 1998.
"Red chips" are commonly defined as those stocks that are listed
on the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong and incorporated in the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), but are owned directly
or indirectly in significant proportions by the Chinese government
or a Chinese state-owned enterprise. At least 35 percent of the
share holdings of "red chips" in the Hang Seng China Affiliated
Corporation (Red Chip) Index are held by state-owned organizations
or provincial or municipal authorities in China. At the end of
June, there were 43 Hang Seng "red chips" with a total market
capitalization of approximately 15 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the IFC China Indexes include three classes of
shares: A-, B- and H- classes, of which only the B-shares and
H-shares are investable by foreigners and included in the IFCI
Index. B-shares, listed either on the Shanghai or Shenzhen stock
exchanges, represented e58 percent of the IFCI market
capitalization on June 30, 1998, while H-shares constituted the
remaining 42 percent of the IFCI China on June 30, 1998. H-shares
do not have large government holdings.
</P>
<P>
According to the announcement, IFC will discontinue the IFCI
and IFCG Index series for Portugal and also remove Portugal from
all regional and composite IFCI and IFCG Indexes on April 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The decision is based on the country's entry into the European
Monetary Union. Portugal is the first country to be selected from
"graduation" from the IFC's emerging markets indexs.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group, financing the private
sector projects in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980804.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia New President Vow New Relationship With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President Andres
Pastrana, after meeting U.S. President Bill Clinton, said here on
Monday that there will be a "new beginning" in his country's
soured relationship with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Today marks a new beginning in the U.S.-Colombian relations.
The years of mistrust are now behind us," Pastrana told reporters
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana, who was elected on June 21 to succeed Ernesto Samper,
said the meeting with Clinton was "candid and full of optimism."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the White House said Pastrana expressed a
commitment to cooperate with the U.S. in fighting drug trafficking
and a desire to peacefully end Colombia's long-running war against
guerrilla insurgents.
</P>
<P>
Clinton pledged to work with Congress to boost U.S. aid to
Colombia for anti-drug efforts, economic development, humanitarian
assistance and private investment, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
The United States also would work with other international
donors and financial institutions to help Colombia's economy,
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"I feel I can speak for both President Clinton and myself when
I say that as of today, an era of change, of positive, productive
change has begun between our two countries," Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
The White House said Pastrana had accepted an invitation from
Clinton to return to Washington for a state visit later this year.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between the U.S. and Colombia has been sour
since the U.S. State Department revoked Samper's travel visa in
1996 and twice "decertified" Colombia as an ally in the anti-drug
war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
