<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Thailand Sign Export Credit Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Export-Import Bank
announced Monday that it had reached an agreement with Thailand to
provide a short-term trade financing program of up to 1 billion
dollars for U.S. exports of goods and services to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The agreement provides short-term insurance coverage for
letters of credit issued by commercial banks and confirmed or
negotiated by U.S. banks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ex-Im Bank Chairman James Harmon, Thailand's Finance
Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda, and Thailand Ex-Im Bank President
Pridiyathorn Devakula signed the agreement in Bangkok on July 31.
</P>
<P>
"Ex-Im Bank has had a mutually beneficial relationship with
Thailand for many years, and I am personally gratified that we
were able to finalize this important agreement," Harmon said in
his announcement of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Ex-Im Bank is an independent government agency that
assists in financing the export of U.S. goods and services to
industrializing and developing markets all over the world by
providing loans, loan guarantees, and insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
