<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-03 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks Between UNSCOM, Iraq Break Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The talks on weapons inspection
between the U.N. chief arms inspector Richard Butler and Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz broke down Monday.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Butler's refusal to go to the U.N. Security Council
to tell the truth about disarmament issue in Iraq led to the
break-down of the talks.
</P>
<P>
This is the first ever break-down of talks between Iraq and
UNSCOM, or the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq,
which indicates that their relations are worsening.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. source told Xinhua that the talks broke down soon after
the second round of talks between UNSCOM headed by Butler and
Iraqi side headed by Aziz started.
</P>
<P>
Then Butler made a phone call to the President of the Security
Council and informed the Security Council of the current
situation, said the U.N. source who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The source said Butler had turned down a proposal from the
UNSCOM delegation that he hold one-to-one talks with Aziz to save
the talks.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM-Iraq talks were scheduled to last two days from
Monday to Tuesday. Under the current situation, the UNSCOM
delegation will probably leave Baghdad on Tuesday morning, a day
earlier than scheduled, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Butler said after the second round of talks that the talks have
reached an impasse and may have collapsed.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know if we are going to meet tomorrow," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the break-down of the talks with
Butler, Aziz said Iraq's position is that it had fulfilled all the
requirement under relevant U.N. resolution long time ago.
</P>
<P>
"All Iraq's weapons of mass destruction have been destroyed and
its ability to produce those weapons were destroyed. The
monitoring system has been established since 1994," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
"I asked Mr. Butler if he has any physical evidence contrary to
the declaration of Iraq... he kept silent," said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Butler proposed a new program of action, but he
rejected it, because Butler was unable to report the truth to the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"What is the use for a new program if you are going to repeat
the same tricks?" Aziz said he asked Butler.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that Iraqi leadership had to assess the situation
and draw necessary conclusions.
</P>
<P>
"There should be a clear end to the suffering of Iraqi people,
there should be a clear end to the lifing of sanctions (off
Iraq)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Iraq is ready to continue cooperation and continue
its obligation, but it cannot do so when UNSCOM is not ready to
report the truth to the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day after the end of the first round of talks,
Aziz criticized Butler for continuing his same old working style
of ignoring essential issues of disarmament, while focusing minor
and insignificant issues to waste time, prolong work and distort
the picture of the situation.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Butler's working style served the U.S. policy which
has the aim to keep the U.N. sanctions in place.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions were imposed in 1990 after Iraq's invasion
of Kuwait. They can only be lifted after the U.N. weapons
inspectors verify that the country is free of weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
