<HEADLINE> Sudanese Govt Extends Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government
announced Monday that it would expand a unilateral cease-fire in
the south starting Tuesday to facilitate the flow of aid in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by senior Sudanese government
officials upon arrival here to attend the Inter-Governmental
Authority on Development (IGAD) ministerial meeting on the
peaceful resolution of the conflict in southern Sudan due to kick
off Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Ethiopian News Agency, head of
the Sudanese government delegation Riech Machar and Foreign
Minister Mustafa Osman said at the airport that the Sudanese
government will make immediate and complete cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire is part of their government's effort to resolve
the conflict peacefully, the senior Sudanese government officials
said.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government earlier agreed on cease-fire to
facilitate food delivery to people affected by drought in
southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The three-day third round talks between the Sudanese
government and the rebel Sudan people's liberation army will be
under the auspices of the 7-nation IGAD. The delegation of the
Sudan people's liberation army led by Deputy Chairman Salva Kir
arrived here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the two sides resumed in Nairobi, Kenya last
October after a three-year hiatus. The two sides held a second
round talks in Nairobi in May this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
