<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Spending Increases as Personal Incomes Go </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Americans kept spending at
a strong pace in June despite their personal incomes posted the
smallest growth in about three years, the Commerce Department
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The personal incomes rose by just 0.2 percent in June, just
half of the 0.4 percent May gain. The big decline reflected in
part a loss of 2 billion U.S. dollars, at an annual rate, in wages
because of the two-month-long General Motors strike, which had not
been settled until last week.
</P>
<P>
The government separately reported that construction spending
rose 1.7 percent in June, the biggest growth in more than a year,
as spending for residential construction rose to an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
Overall construction spending went up to a seasonally adjusted
644 billion dollars in June, the second highest level on record.
The stronger increase reflected a 1.6 percent rise in
single-family homes and a 2.1 percent increase in non-residential
buildings. Construction activity this year has been pushed by
falling interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 percent rise in June incomes matched gains in April
1997 and October 1996 and was the smallest since a 0.1 percent
rise in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of economic
activity, rose at a strong 0.6 percent clip in June. While this
was slower than the 0.9 percent surge in May, that gain had been
the strongest in nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
Even with the strong June increase in consumer spending, the
overall economy slows significantly in the second quarter. The
government reported Friday that the gross domestic product (GDP),
the economy's total output of goods and services, rose at an
annual rate of just 1.4 percent in the spring, a dramatic slowdown
from a 5.5 percent growth rate in the first three months of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Americans' disposable personal income, the amount left over
after paying taxes, was up 0.2 percent in June, the same increase
as the overall income figure.
</P>
<P>
The continued strong growth in spending and the slowdown in
incomes pushed the amount Americans were able to save down to 0.2
percent in June, the lowest level since the government began
keeping monthly statistics in 1959. The savings rate had dipped to
0.5 percent in May after a 1.1 percent rate in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
