<HEADLINE> Britain Urges India, Pakistan to Hold Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The British government Monday
appealed to India and Pakistan to start immediate peace talks in
an effort to resolve their border clashes which have killed more
than 80 people over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Office minister Derek Fatchett said in a
statement issued early Monday, "Recent reports of shootings across
the Line of Control can only add to the already high levels of
tension."
</P>
<P>
"It is therefore important for India and Pakistan to work
urgently to reduce tension between them," said Fatchett, urging
the two countries to set up talks to address their border
incidents.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett also stressed that it is essential that India and
Pakistan "resolve their differences through dialogue." He said
they need to take positive steps on nuclear non-proliferation and
regional security. 
</P>
