<HEADLINE> U.S. Offers no Mediation over Kashmir unless Invited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Monday that it would not offer to mediate between India and
Pakistan over Kashmir unless invited by both sides.
</P>
<P>
"We are willing to assist the parties in this process at the
request of both parties. We don't offer to mediate unless
requested by both sides," State Department spokesman James Rubin
said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
Rubin called on both India and Pakistan to resume talks on
Kashmir that ended with no results in Colombo, Sri Lankan, last
week.
</P>
<P>
The United States "urged the two countries to resume the
senior-level dialogue as soon as possible, and to approach these
talks imaginatively and constructively," he said.
</P>
<P>
There intensive exchanges of fire between Indian and Pakistani
troops on the Kashmir frontier last week, which just tapered off
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The volatility of Kashmir is a stark remainder of the pressing
need for India and Pakistan to resolve their differences. This is
particularly true now following the Indian and Pakistani nuclear
tests, which have significantly raised the states in their
disputes," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States had sent messages to the two parties
urging restraint from "provocative actions."
</P>
<P>
But Rubin said there were no plans for any direct U.S.
intervention. "I'm talking about a diplomatic message from our
government to the Indian and Pakistani governments. Not a new trip
or a new envoy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott's
several meeting with both sides.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Talbott is going to continue to do that, and there
are additional meetings planned in the coming weeks."
</P>
<P>
"That is the diplomatic effort that we're doing, and we believe
there is enough reason for optimism to continue working on it," he
added.
</P>
<P>
But Rubin cautioned reporters not to expect any likely
breakthrough "by any stretch of the imagination." 
</P>
</TEXT>
