<HEADLINE> U.S. Says NATO Approves Plans for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, Aug 3 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) has approved contingency plans for possible
use of military force in the Kosovo crisis, said the United States
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"NATO has now approved a range of contingency plans for the use
of military force," said State Department spokesman James Rubin at
a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that the plans needs to be further refined.
"The secretary-general (of NATO) has requested further refinement
of those initially approved plans that were approved in recent
days," he said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that Rubin's disclosure appeared designed to
pressure Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to halt an
offensive against ethnic Albanian rebels in Serbia's Kosovo
province.
</P>
<P>
"I hope President Milosevic understands this," Rubin noted,
adding that the remaining work by NATO planners "is continuing
apace. And we would expect that work to further refine the options
to be done very, very quickly."
</P>
<P>
Rubin declined to give any details of the contingency plans,
but a meeting in Luxembourg last week, NATO foreign ministers
asked military experts to look at possible preventive deployments
in Albania and Macedonia, which border Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
However, NATO itself has not announced the plans.
</P>
<P>
NATO had indicated that air strikes against Serbia's military
target was an option. But later it did not mention the use of
force any more, which analysts say, is partly because of the
opposition of Russia.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials have said that the campaign of armed violence by
the separatist ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army has also
complicated plans to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said it was up to NATO's political leaders to decide
whether action was needed, but that the two factors making the
military planning necessary, including the refugee problem and the
risk of regional instability, were getting worse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
